animal.description:
Little Benji is a 12 year old mixed terrier breed in need of a understanding and loving forever home. Benji is currently living out his golden years here when he should be in a warm comfy bed in his very own home surrounded by a forever family who loves him unconditionally. Benji has Congestive Heart Failure with a grade 4 heart murmur. He also has some tracheal damage as well. Both cause him to cough often. He is on chronic medications for his heart condition and will require them long term for comfort and continuity of care. He is lively, spunky and enjoys the company of other dogs. He also loves being carried around like the prince he is.

To view the adoptable dogs at our shelter, you must fill out an adoption application found on our website. Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, we are showing dogs on an appointment only basis. Please understand that we are receiving a high volume of applications at this time and are doing our best to address as many as we can. Please be patient. Thank you.

The adoption fee for adult dogs is $250. Aside from the shelter, food and water, exercise and compassion they receive while in our care, this also includes veterinary services such as Rabies, Distemper+Lepto, Bordetella, H3N2/H3N8 Influenza, heartworm testing, fecal exams, preventions and deworming medications. Spays/Neuters are also included as part of the adoption fee as is microchipping. 
Puppies under the age of 6 months have an adoption fee of $350. The veterinary services rendered include puppies first round of vaccines, fecal exams, deworming medications, preventions, and microchipping. Our facility spays and neuters dogs at 6 months of age. If the puppy is adopted prior to his, or her prescheduled surgery date, a $200 spay/neuter deposit will be taken on the day of adoption. This deposit it refundable and will be returned to the adopter once proof of the procedure is returned to the shelter. 
COVID-19 NOTE: Please understand that we are looking for forever home for our pets. We understand that many people have a lot of time on their hands during the COVID-19 pandemic, so this may seem like an ideal time to bring home a new pet. Please be sure you are prepared to give your new pet his, or her forever home once our lives go back to normal. They deserve it. Thank you and stay safe.

animal.description:
NOT YET TAKING APPLICATIONS - NOT YET AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION

NEW INTAKE: January - female - Approx 1.5 years old - 13.8 pounds - Corgi mix

Reason for intake: We were contacted about January by the mother of a young man who found her in a ditch four months ago... skinny, injured and not well. He took her in and nursed her back to health. She has always been very skittish and she actually screamed at times when he would approach... a clear sign of abuse or no socialization. At 18, the young man was just not equipped to give her what she needs. While she was with him, she had an accidental fall between the stairs leading to his second floor apartment and her eye popped out of socket. She was rushed to the ER clinic where they reinserted the eye, but she is blind in that eye. An xray showed also that she broke a rib... BUT the most alarming was that she also had two broken ribs that were healing. This girl has been through so much. She's currently at our vet for spaying, vaccinations, heartworm/fecal testing, etc. When she returns to us, we will work assess her temperament and behavior further before placing her for adoption.

NOT TAKING APPLICATIONS: We are not taking applications yet. We will post when s(he) is ready for adoption. In the interest of fairness, EARLY application submissions will NOT be considered. Please note we cannot respond to messages/emails, etc., on dogs that are NOT yet available for adoption. Please wait until the dog is available for adoption. We appreciate your cooperation and understanding.

animal.description:
Project dog - He needs training (1 1/2 yr old Dachshund mix)Meet Clark aka Jonesy! He is a 1 1/2 yr old Dachshund mix. He original came to us with his mom and other brother in 2019. He was then adopted out to a home with another dog. He is just not doing well with the other dog. He will be ok at times but them he acts out towards that other dog. He turns his frustration into attacking the other dog. He will need an owner that will correct this behavior. We suggest that is an only dog. If someone with another dog is interested we would consider it however, he can be aggressive with other dogs at times, so his new owner needs to make sure they set boundaries, for him.

He is going to need an experience dog owner, that is will to put the time into to training and work on this behavioral issues. We have a trainer lined up that the adopter will be working with. We used this trainer and balanced training method with his brother and had success.

He is no cats, as he wants to do is chase them. He is no kids under 15, as he does not like to be startled when he is sleeping.

He does tend to bark for the first 10 minutes when in his crate or left alone at the house but then does settle in. He also likes to bark while watching out the window when people go by, (we will work with the trainer on this behavior to fix it, so it does not turn into anxiety or aggression).

He is really a nice boy and loves attention from his human, but needs someone that will reinforce boundaries. He is going to be a project dog for the first few months and will need constant training reminds throughout his entire life.

He is crate trained and is house broke.

This animal is current on all age appropriate vaccines, dewormed, microchipped, and spayed/neutered or go home with certificate IF too young to be done. They have also been given flea prevention. Adoption fee is $250.00 If you are interested in adopting this pet please fill out an application.

http://www.ajssearchandrescue.org/adoption-application

animal.description: Rico was found as a stray dog and was lucky to find his way to the League via a Good Samaritan. He is a happy boy with tons of energy. animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Name: Latifah
Age: DOB Approx. 7/15/13
Gender: Female
Breed: Doberman
Weight: 77
Dog friendly: Yes
Cat friendly: TBD
Kid friendly: Yes
House Trained: Doing Well
Crate Trained: Yes
Energy level: Moderate
History: Pulled from an animal control
Adoption Fee: $350

From the Foster:

Latifah is a Adorable Doberman who in True Dobie fashion Loves her person, She Loves to be pet and told what a Good Girl she is , it is so Sweet she will put her head in my lap and sometimes just close her eyes in Total Bliss! Latifah does well with my dogs and she will sometimes engage in a game of chase in my fenced backyard , she also enjoys playing with toys especially the ones that squeak. She also enjoys marrow bones and bully sticks. Latifah is doing well with her housetraining with being let out on a schedule along with her crate training , She does need to be on 2 meds a day one of them helps with this.. Latifah walks nice on the leash and rides nice in the car. She is used to sleeping in my room at night next to my bed on a nice soft dog bed. Latifah is a older gal who is pretty mellow who enjoys being outside with me when the weather is nice whether it is hanging outside with me in my fenced backyard, engaging in a game of chase with her canine buddies or going for a easy going shorter walk. Latifah wants to be by her person as much as possible and she will let you know if she thinks you are not done petting her by gently nudging your hand. Latifah may have some bumps, some weakness in her back legs but she Loves with her whole heart and to see the spark in her eyes, the joy in her step, her little Dobie tail wag is a feeling that just warms your heart! Who is ready to Welcome Latifah into your home and heart and treat her like the Queen she is meant to be!

FROM OUR VET:

Hello! I have some special health needs, but am still considered adoptable.

As expected for a senior gal, I have some arthritis in my hips and spine. I might need NSAID pain management in the future, but for now am on a lifelong regimen on a high quality joint supplement and Gabapentin (for pain). I have some cloudy eyes diagnosed as "nuclear sclerosis" - there is no change to my vision and is simply a normal change due to aging. I have several lumps and bumps, but they have all been documented and evaluated by the SHH Vet and are benign. My adopters should continue to monitor development of any future masses and have them tested to ensure they aren't concerning. A Grade 2 (out of 6) heart murmur was found during an exam; Xrays were taken and evaluated by a cardiologist. Since there are no changes to my heart/lungs, no further workup is needed and it's simply something to be aware of. Lastly, I do experience some urinary incontinence or "leaking". It is well controlled on a medication called Proin that I receive twice daily, so I should remain on this lifelong as well.

animal.description:
STAR is a foster-based rescue. All our rescue animals stay in foster homes until adoption. We do not have a central facility. If you want to meet any of our adoptables please submit an application.

Hi! My name is Snowball! I was born on November 10th and I am on the hunt for my forever home! I am happy, playful and loving life! I LOVE everyone I meet!

I get along and have been raised with other dogs and cats and I love them all! I think playing is so much fun and I am very smart and doing good on crate training so far. I probably will grow to be about 40-45lbs or so just like my mom. I also really like to snuggle . Im up for whatever adventure comes my way and I like to give kisses! If you are interested in meeting a little sweetie like me, please fill out an application asap! www.savingtailsanimalrescue.org

My adoption fee is $300 plus a $50 refundable deposit after I am spayed. I will come up to date on all of my betting, microchipped, and I will come with some food, treats, toys, leash and collar. Thank you for considering me!

All STAR animals come vetted, Up to Date (UTD) on age appropriate shots and testing, spay and neutered (if of age,) and microchipped.

AGE DISCLAIMER:
Unfortunately, most of the orphaned animals that come into our rescue looking for homes don't bring birth certificates. Sometimes we know our pets' ages. Sometimes we don't. So we make our best guess based on the condition of their teeth and the veterinarians best guess.
BREED DISCLAIMER:
Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality,
not
by breed label .
Microchips:
For the safety of our dogs and peace of mind of our fosters and adopters, STAR microchips all dogs prior to adoption with Petlink Microchips. Please understand that all dogs MUST still wear a collar with ID tags (which include your current information) AT ALL TIMES. Please remember, our foster dogs are extremely important to us-- we will always take any of our dogs back, if for any reason you can't keep your adopted dog. Never surrender him/her to a shelter!

animal.description: Woof, woof! I'm so excited you're thinking about adopting a new fur-ever family member! Here are a few things that may help you with your big decision. First, dogs just want to be happy and feel loved. Living inside and being a part of the family is really important to us. A lot of the things you need as humans to stay happy and healthy, us dogs need too. We depend on you for things like vet visits, nutritious food, clean water, social and play time with people and other pets, training classes, toys, and of course, lots of love and attention! Regular baths, nail trims and grooming help us to look and feel our best, while monthly flea and heartworm prevention help us to stay healthy. Did you know that depending on our size and breed, dogs can live up to 20 years? Just think of the wonderful life we could have together!

It’s in his best interest to find a home that has a lot of land for him to run and be busy. He also needs a family that is willing to get him some proper training so that he can be his best self. We recommend that his new home have no children under 15. 
Although Johnny has room to improve, he’s otherwise super smart and we think he’d learn new behaviors quickly. He just needs to be given a chance in the right home with the right people.

animal.description: Sofie Mae is a beautiful and very gentle Great Pyr/Retriever mix that was saved from starvation and surrendered to rescue by a kind-hearted Good Samaritan. She is a friendly and loving girl. She is 'special' needs because she tested positive for heartworm. Sofie Mae began the 'doxy-moxie slow kill method' of treatment with 30 days of doxycycline and monthly doses of moxidectin. The 30 days of doxy has ended and she will receive her 4th dose of moxi in Feb. It is recommended that Sofie be maintained on ProHeart 6, which is a once every six month injection of moxidectin heartworm treatment/prevention. She is an otherwise healthy and happy dog. She is a good service dog prospect. Sofie Mae's adoption fee is a donation to the rescue in the amount of $450.

animal.description: This is Trevi. She was adopted when she was 12 weeks old. She has been returned to us because the original adopter is now battling cancer and downsizing their home from 5 acres to a motor home. She is good with dogs, and children. She is timid and would probably do well with cats. She is house trained but needs work on manners as she likes to place her paws on counters. She is a fast learner and she loves to sleep in the room with you. She is scared of new dogs at first but as long as they respect her space, she is fine. She will cower in a corner or tuck her tail between her legs when they get in her face but she will lift her lips a little to warn them to back up. Currently she is being fostered with 6 dogs and all are co-habitating well. They respect her and therefore no issues.Please apply at muttsandrunts.org/application

Milo was picked up as a stray and brought in on 12/24/2020. He has been wandering in the middle of the road. Milo is a beautiful white and brown mixed dog weighing 69 pounds. We aren't positive what his breed is, but he is very handsome. Milo is a lover and knows about to sit when told. He loves treats and to cuddle with you. Milo will need to be in a home where he can be the only dog or a dog his size or larger(he is not aggressive but he plays rough) and have a fenced in yard where he can run and play. He has a little separation anxiety, so a home where someone will be there most of the time with him. Milo is looking for his perfect forever home, he is neutered and microchipped. His fee is $200.00 with an approved application. He isn't good with cats, too interested, wants to chase them.If interested in adopting a pet from our shelter, please click on one of the following links which will take you to our adoption application. The shelter staff is busy and not often able to answer phone calls so please email us at rchumane@zoominternet.net with any questions. Thank you for your interest! (If you send an email or application our promise is to respond within 24 hours but most of the time it's a much shorter wait. If you don't hear from us, please check your SPAM folder because I promise we have responded.)

animal.description:
For up-to-date info like events, closings, new animals, success stories please LIKE Manchester Animal Shelter on Facebook!


Meet Mr. Claus and Holiday! These boys are a bonded pair of Siberian Husky mixes that must be adopted together. They are 3 years old, weighing around 55 lbs and they do well with other dogs. Yippee! We would say they could live with teens 13+ and would just love playing ball in the yard and going on trail hikes especially in the snow. They do have a decent energy level so they will need a lot of physical activity. They are also EXTREMELY intelligent which comes naturally with the breed. This also makes them sneaky at times so you will need to Husky proof your house and they definitely, as we suggest to all adopters, should go through a basic obedience course to start for these two!

They are such love bugs and I can see them trying to be 55lb lap dogs as well. They should not be left alone for too long because even though they have each other, they are very social and need that interaction with their human(s). Playtime is great for them. They know 'sit', well at least Mr. Claus does, but like I said these two are HIGHLY intelligent as well as super  
 food-motivated, making training so much easier. 

So Holiday is wearing the red collar right now and Mr. Claus is wearing the green. These boys are fun-loving, adventure-ready, affectionate pups looking for their waggly ever after! If you are interested in meeting these studs or would like more info please email canines@manchesteranimalshelter.org



Adoption fee is based on age:
Puppies 8 weeks through 7 months are $400
Dogs 8 months through 7 years are $325
Senior dogs over 8 years are $125 
Seniors for Seniors (Seniors 65+ dogs as week over 8 years): $75

All adoptable dogs are spayed and neutered, have age and time appropriate vaccines, microchipped and heartworm tested. Other medical care provided might include treatments for fleas, ear mites, dental work or infections or other medical conditions. Additional vaccinations and medical care (including puppies Rabies shots if adopted at under 12 weeks of age) will be the responsibility of the adopter.

If you have questions you can call our office at 603.628.3544. To request an application, please email canines@manchesteranimalshelter.org
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Note: As with all of our dogs, we strongly recommend obedience classes for new owner and dog to create a life-long bond with the adopted dog based on trust, respect, and rewarding training experiences. Our shelter dogs are strays and we observe and assess their behavior at the shelter which may be somewhat different in a home environment.

animal.description:
Note: I am deaf.

Hi my name is Neo! I’m 16 years old and 50 lbs! I like humans of all sizes and I live in a foster home with multiple dogs.  I am loving the comfy couch life!

You can come adopt me or even join our foster program to help the humans learn all the awesome things about new dogs like me! Learn more on our website! 

Hope to see you soon! 

What breed am I? Mixed mutt! ODHS does not breed label (unless there’s official paperwork), as studies show it is nearly impossible to tell the exact breed of each dog based off of their appearance.

Educational article:
3/3/3 Rule:
https://www.rescuedogs101.com/bringing-new-dog-home-3-3-3-rule/?fbclid=IwAR2iv5m7fqk3FieO7LOsstGeGsYYV_F1rJOd1BPxaImofLpcinpYsUbFRWs

Adoption Donations are $250 for an adult, $350 for puppies (a dog under one year of age), and $125 for a senior dog (based on the age of the dog). Adoption donations are to be made via cash, and credit/debit card. There is a $5 fee to run cards.

Please remember to bring a collar and leash (non-retractable) with you the day of the adoption. Note: Martingale collars and slip leads are strongly recommended.

Due to COVID19, we aren't having as many open, public adoption events.  Current schedule is pre-determined meet and greet appointments are Wednesday evenings and on Saturdays. 
Our adoption center is located at 3602 Lafayette Blvd, Suite 102, Fredericksburg, VA 22408. It's important that you keep an eye on your emails for any changes or updates during the adoption process.

Visit our website for an application to adopt. 
https://www.olddominionhumanesociety.org/adoption-application

Old Dominion Humane Society is a volunteer based organization. We are run completely by volunteers, who also have full time jobs, so we appreciate your patience.  Currently, the average timeframe for a response to your application is 1 week.

Like us on Facebook "Old Dominion Humane Society"
and be a part of promoting forever homes for dogs in need.
#Adopt #Donate #Foster #Volunteer 

Note: ODHS only adopts to Virginia and surrounding states (including D.C.). A $50 out of state fee applies.

Hi there,

 If you want a dog with a good temperament and loving with young children than I’m your boy.

Friendly eyes, social and outgoing even sensitive to my environment and people around me. I don’t jump, take treats nicely from your hand.

If you want a sense of fun in your life, then come meet me today. I promise to be the best boy in the world.

I absolutely love human companionship, intelligent and lovable.

Licks and Love your pal,

Gunther

Prior to being rescued, many of our dogs have experienced minimal socialization. As a result, there is often an adjustment period when learning about life as a family pet. We typically do not adopt dogs to homes with young children. Homes with older children will be considered on an individual basis. Common skills such as house training and leash walking will often take a little extra time. Patience, understanding and a gentle hand are a must. The great news is, most of these dogs come around rather quickly and being a part of their rehabilitation is an extremely rewarding experience. animal.description:
Hi, my name is Ruby! If you're wondering how I ended up in the shelter, I came in as a stray. When the officer picked me up, they noticed I had a patch of hair missing on my rear. I have been seen by a veterinarian and the hairloss was just from fleas. I have received treatment so now we are just waiting for my hair to grow back in! I'm very upbeat and have a lively personality! I love all people and I'll come running to you for snuggles and to give you kisses when you call for me. You'll learn that all I really want is to be right by your side and be your forever companion. I do cool tricks like jumping in the air to catch treats! I will sit on command and the shelter staff thinks I may possibly be housetrained too. If you have other dogs at home, you can bring them with you to meet me. I have met male and female dogs here at the shelter and did great with both of them! I am a 6 year old Pitbull mix and weighs 65 pounds.

If you are interested in meeting this pet, please contact Chesterfield County Animal Services at (804) 748-1683, option "0", to schedule an appointment. Office staff are available by phone Monday-Friday 8:30 a.m. to 5:00 p.m. and Saturday 7:30 a.m. to 4:00 p.m. The shelter is located at 9300 Public Works Road, Chesterfield, VA 23832.

Meet 7 year old Weasley. 

Weasley is leash trained and crate trained. But must be crated with a friend. 

He loves to lounge outside so a fenced in yard is a must. 

He has high anxiety and is not afraid to use his teeth. 

He is mostly house trained. 

**Weasley is looking for his forever home WITHOUT any kids or visiting kids. 

He does great with other dogs that won't react to his temper tantrums. 

**Experienced dachshund owner is a must.

Weasley's adoption fee will be $375.00 which includes neuter, full vax, microchip, HW & parasite negative, dental (if needed) and any other medical issues treated.

Weasley is currently being fostered in Memphis, TN

Because of volume, we do not answer questions on this page.

House Trained: Mostly
Crate Trained: Yes must be crated with a friend
Kid Friendly: No
Cat Friendly: Unknown at this time

You may apply to adopt at www.tndachshundrescue.com

**Please note the name in the application in the "what you are looking for" section

A little about how the adoption process works:
We are an all volunteer rescue so please be patient with us.
We usually have pre-approved adopters waiting for the right dog so it is best to get your application approved beforehand so you can contact us immediately when you are interested in meeting a potential pet.

You will be contacted once the app is processed for a home visit.
If you are already approved and see a dog you are interested in, please contact your adoption coordinator.


Check our FaceBook page at: https://www.facebook.com/tndachshundrescue/

MEET LEIA

***POTENTIAL ADOPTER LOCATION REQUIREMENT- Our general adoption area is with a 50 mile radius of our Friendsville Home base - zip code  37737*** You can check to see if you fit within the radius at https://www.zipcodesoft.com/zip-codes-in-a-radius

Our adoption applications can be found online at www.tapsusa.org

Who am I? I'm  Leia!
Where did you meet TAPS?  At a local shelter. My former owners took me to the shelter because I had an injured knee that they couldn't afford to fix my skin allergies. 
How old are you?  I am around 5-6ish years old
Tell us about yourself!  My knee had surgery and is on the mend and I am on some awesome new special food that seems to have my allergies under control.  I love to run and play and especially really like other dogs to hang out with.  I am silly and affectionate and have a zest for life!

Check out some videos!  (you'll need to copy and paste the links)

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1EhOVeSvFMPUb1j_4oFPl6dcuXovpCD46/view?usp=sharing

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1qdnPVU2HSY_gM1Y2BsXeGX6nYKx9edHl/view?usp=sharing

I weigh approximately:  48lbs

To adopt one of our animals, the first step is filling out an adoption application at www.tapsusa.org,  Please make sure you get a confirmation that your application has been submitted. IF YOU ARE FILLING OUT AN APPLICATION ON A PHONE OR PAD, HOLD THEM SIDEWAYS TO SEE ALL OF THE FIELDS.  IF YOU ARE NOT ABLE TO SUBMIT THE APPLICATION AT THE END, IT MEANS YOU HAVE MISSED A FIELD SOMEWHERE AND NEED TO REVIEW THE APPLICATION AGAIN.

Where can you meet me after you are contacted that you may be a good fit for me?

OPERATION ADOPT TN
c/o Friendsville Animal Center
706 Kiser Station Road
Friendsville, TN  37737

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY

All animals are spayed/neutered, current on age appropriate vaccinations and microchipped before they go to new homes because that's the responsible way to keep them all safe.

To adopt one of our animals, the first step is filling out an adoption application at www.tapsusa.org Please make sure you get a confirmation that your application has been submitted. 

We only adopt to local homes  in the immediate vicinity because we utilize our volunteer force to process home visits.  Photos of your home, letters of reference are not acceptable which is why we only adopt locally. Only in very rare circumstances do we adopt out of area.  Examples of this would be finding the perfect home for a senior animal or one that has other special needs that we have not been able to place locally for an extended period of time.

animal.description:
Laci is a sweetheart.  She is 5 yrs old and about 38 lbs in size.  She has a typical heeler nature which includes being a good protector and worker.  Heelers like having a job and Laci is loyal to her family to not only love but, guard them against strange things or people.

We know a bit about her background and she has lived both inside and out.  She is housebroken and lived in different family situations in her past.  We are looking for a home where she can get daily exercise off leash.  Being totally an inside dog tends to make her over protective of her family and she doesn't take well to strangers or strange dogs approaching.  We feel she is ideally suited to a home outside a city where traffic and unfamilar folks are not a common occurrence.  As you can see by her photos she has a kind heart.  We are very fond of her and her sister!

She is fully vetted, microchipped, been heartworm treated and requires heartguard protection monthly which is not expensive.  Laci has a sister with the same personality and tendencies.  

Other dogs can be an issue with Laci but, she did get along with an existing passive dog in her first adoption with no problems.

We are a rural shelter with high intakes.  As a result, the shelter dogs are not guaranteed safety. We do our best but, we need help.
ADOPTION FEES APPLY-  Dogs $85-$125.  Cats $60-$80.  (We are not set up for credit or debit payments.)

Please visit or make an inquiry by calling this number 606-663-4998.  Leave a message on voicemail if you miss the staff.  Your calls are VERY IMPORTANT to us!
The shelter is open Monday thru Friday from 9 - 3 p.m. except Thursdays (closed).  Saturday hours are by appt.  

After hours appts can be arranged with advance notice and an approved application.  We want to accommodate! 

For an alternate phone, call 859-948-0371.  We are glad to answer any questions.   Adoption rates are low and include a spay or neuter and rabies. Surgeries are mandatory!

Shelter is located at 121 Echo Hollow Rd - Clay City, Ky  40312

animal.description:
Molly came into rescue with Lady when their owner moved into an apartment and was told by the landlord that he could not keep them. We believe Lady to be lab/terrier mix. From what we were told by her owner, Molly had a rough start early in life. She was originally owned by someone else who moved out of state and left her tied outside without food or water. Molly was saved by this owner and given a decent life. Molly has had 2 litters of puppies, who all found homes but Molly wants her chance to have a stable, loving home. Molly is approx 3 years old and is really a sweet girl. She gets along well with kids and dogs of all ages and sizes. Cats are unknown and we do not know if she has ever had any experience with cats. She is very gentle and enjoys attention. Molly is crate trained and will go out but we never guarantee any of our dogs to be housebroken. Molly weighed 46.6 pounds at her vet visit on 1/21/21. She is spayed and ready to find a family to spend her days and nights cuddling with. She is a somewhat (initially) shy but happy girl ready to share her affections with a family of her own. Molly, unfortunately, tested positive for heartworms but has started the monthly ivermectin treatment, which is very inexpensive and easy to give. Her new owner will just need to keep her on a monthly ivermectin dose until she receives a negative heartworm test. This can be a slow process but it does work and we have successfully treated many heartworm positive dogs this way through the years.Molly also has some leg deformities and issues on her right side. We did x-rays on back leg as the knee is very unstable and routinely pops in and out. Vet said the surgery to fix can be very costly but she can be managed with a pain management regimen. Vet is unsure if this is something that she was born with or if it is the result of a traumatic injury (such as a hit by car) at some point in her life but eventually, she will probably develop arthritis and difficulties walking, although that is probably many years down the road. She runs, walks and gets around normally right now although she will, occasionally limp. Although we understand that these issues greatly impact her adoptable "appeal", we hope that someone can see past physical limitations and will see the beauty of her soul. This girl is so loving and kind and will make an amazing companion!
Molly''s adoption fee will be $175 and will help to cover her vetting and cost of care while with us. If interested in giving Molly her forever home, please complete and submit our adoption application and interest via email. You may also FB message, text only to (352)215-3260.(phone calls will not be answered or returned from this number but it is the best and quickest option for contact) or call 352-493-1255 (leave message if no answer).

animal.description:
Sheena is a new arrival from Rosebud Reservation who is just sweet as pie! She is approximately 5-6 years old and weighs approximately 40-50 pounds.

Sheena is good with other dogs, but not one to play with them - she prefers to watch and hang out instead. Sheena has been exposed to cats and just wants to leave them alone and is cautious when they approach her.

Sheena loves everyone she meets - she loves to get ear scratches from all ages. Occasionally she will jump up (super gently) to receive additional attention, but is very good about getting down when reminded.

Sheena has been polishing her basic commands and doing well - she is kennel trained and has not had any accidents in the house in her foster so far.

Sheena is fully vetted including vaccinations, heartworm tested negative, spayed, microchipped, and current on her flea/tick/heartworm/deworming preventatives. Sheena's adoption donation fee is $250.00

We realize that people are looking for a predominant breed or breed mixture, but visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of our dogs we are only guessing at the predominant breed or breed mix.  We encourage you to select your new companion by considering each dog's individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on a breed label that is only a guess.

If you're interested in adopting, please visit our main website at www.sarahstreasuresrescue.net for adoption information and our application!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact Ruth (rpriestley@sciotodowns.com) for more information about this pet.Bianca's adoption donation is $325 and is being fostered in Central Ohio. She has been spayed, microchipped, received her rabies, distemper/parvo, bivalent canine influenza and bordetella vaccines, tested negative for heartworms and started on prevention, as well as flea prevention. She has also had a dental cleaning. Bianca requires a home with a secure, physically fenced yard and a companion dog in the home.

Bianca came into rescue from a commercial breeder when she was no longer useful to them. She is approximately 8 year old Maltese who is making big strides in rescue. Bianca is learning to walk on a leash but still needs a fenced yard and a companion dog in the home. She does well on housetraining if kept on a schedule but continues to improve. Bianca does well riding in a car but is still learning to do stairs. Bianca requires a patient home that will give her the time to decompress and learn about her new home with the help of a companion dog.PLEASE NOTE: If you are viewing this biography on a website other than the Ohio Fuzzy Pawz website, not all information transfers to partner websites in some instances. If you go to the individual webpage of our dogs, you will be able to get more information each dog.

Visual breed identification in dogs can be unreliable so, in many cases, we are only guessing at the predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

Our Adoption Process

The adoption process has several steps involved.

Please review prior to submitting an application.
Our adoption process is detailed here:

http://www.ohiofuzzypawz.com/info/adoption

Our volunteers work very diligently to process each application and we try to ensure that we are making the best match possible for each dog. We do not schedule meetings with dogs until an application has been approved. It can take up to a few weeks to process an application or as little time as a few days, from the time you submit an application, please be prepared to adopt as we cannot hold dogs.

Special Requirements

Some dogs may have special requirements (for example, medications, a fence) -- if you apply for a dog, please be sure to read over the biography completely to see if there are any special needs and if you're home would be suitable. If we indicate on the dog's biography that a fence is required, this means your home must have a physical fence. Other dogs may require a "strong vet reference" which indicates that we are looking for a home that has a documented history of veterinary care with previous pets.

The first step in our process is to submit an online adoption application at www.ohiofuzzypawz.com/forms. The application MUST include the personal references and veterinary, grooming, and landlord references (if applicable) and their respective contact information. If you do not include the references and the contact information, your application will be delayed as it CANNOT be processed. Once the references have been successfully completed, a home visit is then scheduled when a rescue representative can meet all members of the family or residents of the home.
No application is approved prior to the home visit being done.
At that point, the Directors will discuss any and all applications on a foster dog and make a selection--in many cases, there are multiple applications for each dog, so please be understanding that our only priority is the successful placement of each of our foster dogs.

Out of State Adoptions

We do adopt out of state to outstanding applicants, however, our process requires a home visit, so out of state adoptions can take longer.
We do not ship our dogs, adopters should be prepared to pick up the dog in Central Ohio.

animal.description:
Meet Griffin - a stunning boy who is looking forward to a new life of being a pampered pup!  Griffin arrived to us from the reservation and has adjusted well to the good life.  He's approximately 2 years old and best guess is a mixed Golden/Shepherd/Lab type of pup.  He weighs approximately 65-70 pounds.

Griffin does well with other dogs of all sizes but seems to play better with females.  Griffin has been introduced for cats and he didn't show any aggression towards them, but he will bark at them.

Griffin loves people and tries hard to please.  He's a smart boy who likes to know what you expect and happily obliges when he understands.  Griffin is working on his basic commands and leash manners.  Griffin has been around some children and done but does not currently live with any.  He does occasionally forget his size and needs reminders to 'be gentle'.

Griffin has mastered kennel training and does well at house training - however, he needs to be reminded not to mark territory when first in a new place.  His neuter will help this some, but continued training will continue to improve his understanding that it is not okay inside. 

Griffin has a goofy, playful nature about him when he gets comfortable and loves to bounce around and wrestle once comfortable.  He is discovering what toys are and is starting to incorporate these as he plays!

Griffin has started on his vet work and will be completing it shortly.  Upon going into his new approved forever home, Griffin will be up to date on vaccinations, heartworm tested negative, microchipped, neutered, and current on his flea/tick/heartworm/deworming protocols.  Griffin's Adoption Donation Fee is $300.00

**WE ARE CURRENTLY DOING ADOPTIONS BY APPOINTMENT ONLY. YOU MUST CALL TO SCHEDULE AN APPOINTMENT IF YOU'RE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING. PLEASE LEAVE US A VOICEMAIL IF YOU ARE UNABLE TO REACH US. THANK YOU FOR YOUR PATIENCE AND UNDERSTANDING.- CCDP STAFF**

Hi there. My name is Brutus. I'm about 10 years old and I weigh a little over 40 lbs. 
I was surrendered to the pound through no fault of my own and I am now looking for a new loving family to join. 
I am very sweet. I love people and I get along well with other dogs, but would do best in a home without cats. 
In am said to be housebroken and I do well with keeping my kennel clean at night. 
If you're looking for a sweet dog to add to your family, please consider adopting me.

Our adoption fee is $150.00. The pound DOES NOT accept checks for adoption fees. We're able to accept cash for adoption OR Visa/ Mastercard/ Discover Card. A convenience fee of 2.39% will be applied to all credit/ debit card adoptions. If you intend to do a foster-to-adopt, the fee must be cash. ALL dogs/puppies adopted from our shelter will receive their parvo distemper vaccine, bordetella vaccine, rabies vaccine (if aged at 12 weeks or older), be dewormed with a 3 day course of panacur dewormer, be microchipped, receive their current Ohio dog license and will be spayed or neutered. ALL DOGS/PUPPIES WILL BE SPAYED OR NEUTERED unless a health issue prohibits the surgery from being performed. Not all dogs posted for adoption are spayed/ neutered yet. If you're driving a long distance to adopt, please verify that the vetting process has been completed and dog you're interested in adopting is still available for adoption. The above mentioned vetting is all included in your adoption fee. The adoption fee and what is included in the adoption fee is NON-NEGOTIABLE.

Adoptions MUST be done at the pound and in person as there is paperwork to fill out and an adoption contract that must be signed by the adopter. This means you must be willing to travel to our shelter to adopt.

IF the dog you're interested in adopting has medical conditions or injuries which require medical treatment, we ask that you help with the medical bills so we can continue to help the dogs coming in who need additional vet care.
We are a county run shelter, therefore we cannot control our intake or the health or behavior of the dogs that come in to our shelter.

Although we try our hardest to place all of our adoptable dogs, there are certain circumstances in which any dog in our care could be euthanized at any time and without further notice (IE: sudden untreatable medical condition or injury, temperament or behavioral problems which may not be apparent when the dog first arrives, lack or space, etc.), therefore all dogs at our shelter should be considered urgent. The adoption of a more highly adoptable dog will mean more time for the less adoptable dog in the kennel next to him!

Shelter hours are: Monday-Friday: 8 am- 4 pm
Saturday: 8 am - 11 am.
Sunday: 8 am - 11 am.
Adoptions are always welcome during hours of operation. We will make special arrangements for adoptions in advance.
There is nobody in the office on Saturday and Sunday, so therefore we are unable to answer or return phone calls over the weekend.

Can't adopt a dog? We would love to have more volunteers who are able to spend time with our dogs! The dogs LOVE going for walks and the socialization and exercise helps make the dogs more adoptable.

Contact information:
8455 County Home Road
Lisbon, OH 44432
(330)424-6663
Email: hpecorelli@ccclerk.org

animal.description:
Meet Pinky! Pinky is around 1 year old and 36lbs. She recently had a pin put in her leg to fix a fracture. She is super sweet and loves everyone.

Hi I'm Pinky, and I'm pretty perfect! Check out my resume: 
 
Born: in Alabama and I think the snow is GREAT. 

Skills: go potty outside, hangout by myself inside and outside of my crate, know exactly what dog beds are for, chew and nap while my foster parents work, make friends easily (even the cats), share my food and toys, take baths, snore, give hugs and kisses, smile a lot, spread peace and joy. 

I'm gentle and calm, but also curious about the big world out there! I'm a happy girl who loves to play, but I also love relaxing and being comfy. I'm looking for a home that can make me as happy as I know I can make them. I can't wait to meet you!

Interested in this sweet dog? Apply today at http://www.underdogpetrescue.org/dog-application

**Please note: Our animals live in foster homes throughout the Madison area. We do not have a shelter where animals are available for daily viewing. Applying is the first step in our process.**

Dogs from Underdog Pet Rescue come with the following medical care already provided:
Spay/Neuter
Rabies, Distemper, and Bordetella Vaccinations (as age appropriate-puppy adopters may need to cover some vaccine boosters)
Heartworm Test (for dogs over 6mo)
Microchip
Deworming
Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative
Any other necessary medical treatment as recommended by veterinarian

Our adult dog adoption fee is $300. Our puppy (under 5 mo) is $375. Our senior dog (over 8 yrs) is $250.

*Please note that all breeds noted are estimates or best guesses. We very rarely have information on our animals' actual breeds since they often come to the shelters we work with as strays*

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Lexus!

The GHS thinks I am awesome because I LOVE people and completely win over every person I meet. I like to lean into people as they pet me and sometimes even end up in their lap-the closer the better! My foster mom says I am the quietest husky ever and make an excellent work from home buddy, I just cuddle up at your feet while you work. You would never know I am 9 years old as I love to run around and play and I look so cute when I get the zoomies! I am also incredibly smart and very treat motivated!

My new family should know that although I love affection I can get a little nervous when being handled in more formal settings, such as for the vet or for nail trims. My foster mom has been working hard to help me get more comfortable with my paws being handled and I have come a long way already-she can now trim my nails while I am lying down! I am looking for a family who will use positive training methods to continue to work with me on being more comfortable with certain handling. Don't worry, I am very eager to work for my treats!
I have been diagnosed with diabetes, but am well managed on my daily insulin and special diet. For my insulin, as long as there is lots of peanut butter and cheese whiz involved, with two people it has not been a problem for my fosters! I am looking for a family that has knowledge or experience with diabetic dogs and is willing to continue this medical care.

I have met several children in foster and really like the attention they give me. I could live in a home with respectful children who know not to hug me or touch my paws until I am more comfortable. I can be a little unsure around other dogs but once I am more comfortable I like to play. I could do well as the only dog in the home or live with another calm, respectful dog. I have lived with cats before and done well.

I do not have the best hearing but my foster mom has started teaching me hand signal commands and I already know sit, down, paw, stay, and come in hand signals-that's how smart I am! I am such an affectionate, smart, playful girl and everyone who has met me loves me. If you are looking for a loyal best friend, I am definitely your girl!

If you are interested in adopting me, please visit the Guelph Humane Society's "How to Adopt" page (https://guelphhumane.ca/adopt/how-to-adopt/) and submit an Expression of Interest (EOI) form as soon as possible so you don't miss out on taking me home!

animal.description: Hi! My name is Delgado. I was rescued in Puerto Rico before arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I am a very good boy but I would be happiest if I could be the puppy king of the castle in my new home. I do not like to play with other dogs and I am much more interested in receiving human affection. Cats and children are also not my favorite so if you're an experienced single dog owner or couple, I'd love to meet you! I would be happiest if I could have a home with a big yard for me to run around in and an owner who loves to play with toys or have a rousing game of fetch. I'm also a huge cuddle bug and would love nothing more than snuggling up next to you on the couch. I could use some continued training once I find my furever home but I appear to be potty trained at this point, as I keep my kennel very clean. I would love to have an active owner who wants to take me for lots of walks and maybe even a swim! If you're looking for an activity buddy, I am just the perfect pick!

animal.description:
Hi - Hope you are having a great day!  I love days when I get to hang out with my humans- they are the best!  My name is Tank (sort of fits me don't you think?) I am a Pittie mix, about 3 years old and weigh in at a solid 65lbs. My foster dad says I am a handsome boy with my silver coloring! I am looking for my FOREVER FAMILY!  You see, I was dumped off by my family one night.  My foster dad heard a loud truck pull up outside his house at like 4am and, in the morning, there I was waiting by the front gate.  I even had a collar on with my name on it.  Not sure why my old family didn't want me anymore - I tried to be the best boy.  Whatever the reason, I have come to understand that it really was a day that changed my life for the better because my foster family is amazing. They tell me I am a good boy and have gotten me all ready to find a home of my very own!
 
What else would you like to know about me?  My foster dad says I am a sweet boy who loves attention. I am a medium to high energy and will need my new family to be active.  We can walk and hike and play together! My rescue is looking for people that have experience with my breed.  I haven't had much training so I’m looking forward to my new family helping me be all I can be!  We think a teen/adult home would be best for me, just because I am a big boy and don't want to accidentally knock any kids over....I would feel terrible!  I am fostered with other dogs and do fine with most of them.  I can be  a little choosy about my canine buddies so I might be best as an only pet- king of the castle so to speak. My foster dad says no cats- they just want to make me chase them!  I am crate trained and learning to walk on leash (I do pull sometimes) and coming along with my house training.  It's all new to me, but with a good, consistent routine and positive reinforcement, I know I will learn quickly!  I am a work in progress!!
 
You'll be happy to hear that I have been neutered and am up to date on my vaccines, I am also micro-chipped and flea-tick and heartworm preventative. If you are a pittie lover who has experience with my breed and are looking for a new BFF, please email  ...Nancy at campellones58@gmail.com................. and she'll zip you out an application.  I’m not perfect yet, but I’ll work hard to be perfect for you.  My adoption fee is $350.
 
Like us on facebook: https://www.facebook.com/PawsClawsNewEngland
Follow/tag us on Instagram: @pawsclawsne or #pawsclawsne

animal.description:
Rex, short for T-Rex, is a 4 year old Mastiff/Lab mix. He is a big guy weighing 110 pounds. He thinks he's a small dog and likes to sit on the furniture with you and loves to sleep in the bed. He gets along with most other dogs but does like to be more of a leader. He does not do well with cats. Rex is very smart, he knows sit and down and stay (a little). He is housetrained. He walks on a leash well but has lots of energy. Rex is looking for a home preferable with a fenced yard (higher fence, 6 ft), or someone that is active and can handle his energy level. He also needs a home with an experienced dog owner, hopefully one with large dog experience. He can be stubborn at times and needs someone who can be a firm pack leader. He would certainly benefit and enjoy additional obedience training. Due to his size and energy level, Rex is best suited for a home with older or no children. Rex is neutered, current on all vet work and microchipped.

LOCAL INQUIRIES ONLY PLEASE

animal.description:
Get ready to fall in love! Pinky is about 60 pounds of happiness and joy. He enjoys being with people or other well behaved dogs. He would probably do best in a home with a doggie play buddy to wear off some of his energy or in an active household. While he has good stamina and lots of energy, he also loves spending time on the couch with someone. (We melted the first time he put his big head on our shoulder!)
Pinky will pull at your heart strings with his affectionate ways. He wants to be included in everything you do, but can be distracted with a good Nylabone or a filled peanut butter bone.
This guy would be best in a family of adults and maybe older teens. Younger children would be ok too after Pinky goes to basic training to contain his excitement around smaller children.
Pinky enjoys a comfy bed and delicious food. He does well sleeping in a crate at night, but sometimes needs a potty break. When he does bark, it's usually because he needs to go to the restroom or wants a drink of water.
Squeaky toys get him excited but he needs the super chewer kind or he ends up deconstructing them. He likes playing frisbee but doesn't always release it on demand.
Running through puddles is another of his favorite pastimes and rain usually doesn't bother him. He likes every dog he's ever met: big, small, male and female. He is curious about cats, but we don't recommend a house with cats. If he's with another dog, Pinky likes to run and play chase. If he's alone he prefers being inside to spending time in the back yard (and who wouldn't with his light colored coat?).
Pinky would enjoy going to a training class, since he's a very smart boy and wants to please. He does walk well on a leash or harness (no pulling unless he sees a squirrel).
Pinky loves you already and hasn't even met you yet!
If you are interested in Pinky and would like to fill out a Dog Adoption Application, please go to: http://www.homelesspets.net/adoption-forms/dog-adoption.php . Submitting an application does not obligate you to adopt from us but it initiates contact with us and gets the process started. If you have questions prior to filling out the application, email us at HOPEDogCommittee@groups.io and a volunteer will get back to you.

animal.description:
Please read about King before applying.   King is a very friendly, handsome big bouncy boy.  He is a little over a year old and has developed into a strong overly energetic puppy that had no training growing up.  King is smart and loves to please and will sit, stay and give paw for a treat.  If you see him as a dog that you would love to have (and who wouldn’t), please know that you must be willing to commit to continue with his training to help him become a great dog and companion as he still has a long way to go.   He needs lots of exercise, not just put outside to run around on his own, but long walks or someone that is willing to play ball with him for long periods of time. A tired dog is a good dog. 

Without  time invested in him, King will be destructive left on  his own.  He is learning to walk on a leash but is still a strong puller.   King is a diamond in the rough, but he needs a strong, experienced leader, he is definitely not for the first time dog owner or for someone that cannot handle his strength.  The continuation of his training is a must so make sure that you have the time, patience and can make the commitment to do this before you apply.  

King is neutered, vaccinated (including bordetella) and microchipped. His adoption fee is $215.00. (cash or check only, we are unable to accept credit cards)

King is kindly sponsored by: Barb Smith in memory of Gary Smith, Dan Courtine  in honor of Amy Peterson, David and Patricia Nye, Tina and James McCroskey, Melford Swanson, Suzanne and former NCCR residents, Tillie Mae and Bron Bron, Dave and Nancy Nuzzo, Joseph Incavo, Cathy and David Ferguson, and Mo and Andrew Broadbent in memory of Kofi. Thank you everyone!

If you think you might be interested in adopting, your first step should be to complete an adoption application. APPLICATION to ADOPT: Copy and paste this link in your browser to view and complete the application https://forms.gle/NghtT4WTNiaZu7Cg9. You can also select the link, right click and choose open in a new window.

We do adopt out of state, however we do not transport or ship dogs.  Potential adopter must be able and willing to travel to the Rescue to meet the dog they are interested in.  

*PLEASE double check all of the phone numbers that you provide as if they are incorrect, we will be unable to process your application.  Please also let your references know that someone from NCCR will be calling them. Most adoption team members call from their personal phone so advise your references that there may be an unknown number or a private number calling them.  

NYS Registration #RR028.

animal.description:
Finn is a very handsome, big, young Pyr boy looking for his furever home. Finn has been very well-loved and is currently living with his brother. Like many littermates they are not getting along as they get older. Finn has done well with his minimal exposure to other dogs and as always proper introductions will set him up for success. He is house trained and knows sit, stay and off. He’s looking forward to learning more and, like all youngsters, will need continued training to help him reach his full potential! Finn is still curious, and the occasional shoe or napkin will fall victim to puppy chewing :) Finn likes leisurely walks and is working on his leash skills. He enjoys playing fetch and then lounging around for the rest of the day. Finn does well meeting new people and is gentle with kids. His favorite thing ever is to lay on your legs while getting brushed. Like a good Pyr, Finn will alert you of incoming danger - squirrels, mailmen, you-name-it! He’s a true protector of his home and he’s proud of that. Finn is pretty calm for his age and wants to be with his humans wherever they go. He is sure to quickly find his way into your heart the minute he sits at your feet and gently puts his nose to yours to remind you to pay attention to him. When falling asleep, he will let out a sweet and hilarious sigh after a long day protecting his pack :) Finn is a big, wonderful boy with even bigger potential, so if you’re a committed family, looking for a young Pyr to add to your pack, apply for handsome Finn today!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
~ THIS IS A COURTESY POST ~ PLZ DO NOT CONTACT MASSPAWS ~
To adopt this special dog, please complete an ARK application by copying and pasting this link into your browser: https://tiny.cc/ARK-Application
Note: For some ARK dogs, a point of contact name and email will be included in the bio, see below.

Meet Shelby! She is a 1-year old, 55-pound American Staffordshire Terrier female located in Norton, MA. She’s hoping to be adopted before her 2nd birthday which is on April 14th! Shelby is a pretty red head who’s up to date on all her shots including heartworm and flea & tick prevention. She is spayed, house trained, and crate trained. She does perfect in her crate overnight and when left alone. 

Shelby enjoys chew bones and sets the record for quickly ripping out the stuffing from her soft toys! She loves her walks and her favorite season is summer when she can run around outdoors and hike. Shelby also loves car rides (#ShelbyGT500) but does get car sick, so travelling on an empty stomach is best for her. 

She spends her days sleeping especially in winter, but between naps she loves playing in the snow. Watch out around 4 pm however because that’s when she peps up and gets her zoomies! And she’s smart, too! Shelby understands most basic commands such as sit, stay, leave-it, wait, down, and “in your crate.” She wants you to know that she’s not a fan of rain.

Shelby gets along well with other dogs and likes playing with them. She lives with a chi right now, but prefers dogs her size or larger as she tends to be a little rough with smaller dogs and does not understand the size difference. If she does go to a home with other dogs she should eat her meals and treats alone. 

Shelby is being rehomed because she is too anxious around small children. Her current family has an active 5-year old who just wants to play, but Shelby prefers her personal space and quiet time. She is great with adults, but the little ones are overwhelming! Therefore, Shelby would do best in a family without small children, respectful kids 12 and up are a better match. 
 
Though nervous at times, Shelby now has a calmer outlook on life since taking prescription medication. This should be continued at least for a few months until she is adjusted to a new home, though there’s no guarantee how long meds will be needed. ARK trainer and friend Maura Porter of Clear Skies Training has worked with Shelby and agrees she’s a good all-around dog but one that’s not suited for young kids.
 
Shelby has one nipping incident in her otherwise loving nature. Last year, Shelby had a growth removed, which required her to wear the cone of shame for two months. When her current mom leaned into the cone for a kiss, Shelby became startled and nipped. Lesson learned, no kissing a dog in a cone!  Otherwise she has been nothing sweet.

Re-cap: Love bug who appreciates “me time.” Best for kids 12+, no cats, compatible dog. Please apply here: https://tiny.cc/ARK-Application #ARKforShelby #JustSaveThem

animal.description:
This sweet guy is Granger, 1-2 years old and 67lbs, and he is deaf. He is underweight and had been feeding on rocks and dirt. Poor Granger is scared of being touched due to feeling like he is going to be hit. When he sees you mean no harm, he loves pets and to be loved on. He is still wary but learning he is in good hands now. Upon gaining weight, he will be a big guy. He is pit bull terrier mixed with bulldog or great dane. The person who found him said his own dogs tried to attack Granger but all he did was walk away with no aggression shown. He would do best in a home with another dog to give him confidence and show him the ropes.

Please call the shelter with questions, 319.753.8389... all animal inquiries must be made by telephone to the shelter during our hours listed below.  Thank you! 
****************
Chanci is an approximately 2-3 year old Boxer mix  that is currently available for adoption at the Des Moines County Humane Society in Burlington, Iowa.  A meet and greet would be required with any other dogs that would be in a potential adopter's home.  Chanci needs a home without cats.  Additionally, she loves, loves, LOVES her toys so much that young kids are probably not a good idea for her.  Chanci knows how to sit and takes treats pretty softly.  She is a sweet and loving dog.  Poor Chanci has had it rough this past month and is in desperate need of a family that can turn her life around.... Read below for Chanci's story... 

Some background on Chanci:  

A very kind couple were on a trail hike in Lake Geode when they came across this sweet girl trying to stay warm in a snow-covered hole.  Her pawprints have frostbite and she was absolutely freezing and probably would not have made it much longer out there.  As you can see in the pictures, the young man managed to somehow get her in a backpack and he CARRIED her out 2 miles out of the trails on his back.  She is very thin and appears to have previously had a couple litters of pups.  Another person reports having seen the dog 3 days ago as she was driving through Geode.  She stopped and turned around but sadly, could not find her.  We believe our sweet girl has been out there for at least a week.  A big thank you to the angels who brought her to us.  And remember, we have no idea if she is a lost dog or was dumped.  This poor girl was so defeated and sad when found but is now gaining her security back with the help of our staff.  She is now a happy, much more outgoing girl.

******
All dog adoptions include the spay/neuter, heartworm test, first two sets of basic immunizations as well as a rabies vaccine and a vet visit. Our adoption fee is $125.00 and all dogs do require an approved application. 

Please note our adoption hours: Tues-Fri from 3-6pm and from 1-5 on the weekends. We are closed on Mondays!

animal.description:
Age: Estimate 7 - 10 years
Weight: 54 lbs (as of 01/04/21)

Location: RI

This dog has been spayed/neutered, is up to date on shots, on heartworm preventative and is microchipped.

DiGi is a sweet and gentle girl!

This beautiful lady is going to be the perfect addition to someone's home! We are thinking sweet DiGi is a Shepherd mix but we aren't sure of her age, and are guessing about 7-10 years old. She is a new mom that recently weaned eight healthy and happy pups.

She is affectionate with everyone she meets including kids of all ages. Her foster mom says DiGi is always gentle and affectionate with her three-year-old grandson. DiGi is just coming off exercise restriction, as she was on heartworm treatment, and while there are other dogs at her foster home, she hasn't interacted with them on a daily basis. We thus don't know how she is with other dogs but suspect she will be ok as she is so even-tempered and gentle. She also lives with cats, but hasn't spent too much time with them but is unengaged when she sees them.

DiGi is a smart girl that is house trained and crate trained. Looking for a walking partner? If so, DiGi is the dog for you! She rides well in the car and would love to join you on a walk or hike. A fenced yard would be ideal so DiGi could run and play safely, but if that's not available she'll need lots of leash walks and opportunities for off-leash play in a fenced area. An obedience course would be great for DiGi; it will help teach her good manners and commands, further socialization with other dogs and people, and will help build that very important bond between a dog and her human.

DiGi is a gentle happy girl who just wants a loving forever home. Can you make her dream come true? Fill out an application today and let her know that you'd love to have her join your family!

DiGi's story: We don't know much about this sweet girl other than she was found as a pregnant stray. She is doing great and can't wait to meet you!

Medical Note: This dog has been treated for heartworm disease with melarsomine injections. Once treatment is completed and the dog tests negative for microfilaria, the dog will be cleared to resume normal activity and able to be adopted. Untreated heartworm disease can cause lasting damage to the heart, lungs and arteries, and can affect the dog's health and quality of life even after the parasites are gone, possibly presenting as medical complications and/or new conditions in the future. This dog showed no symptoms of heartworm disease before or during treatment. A good resource for more information on heartworm disease is: https://www.heartwormsociety.org/pet-owner-resources/heartworm-basics.

Medical Note: This dog tested positive for exposure to ehrlichia while in SOS foster care. This does not mean that this dog had ehrlichia. This dog is/has been asymptomatic while in SOS care and was preventatively treated with a 28-day course of doxycycline. Please see here for more information on ehrlichia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ehrlichiosis_(canine).

Medical Note: This dog's teeth are badly worn; both maxillary and mandibular incisors and canines are worn to the gum line. This is likely from living with no flea/tick control and chewing on her fur to bring herself relief. Her back molars are still functional but show some wear. While she has been in our care, she has been eating and drinking fine, and has not shown any signs of discomfort. This should be monitored and extractions may be recommended in the future if discomfort is noticed. Additionally, mature cataracts were observed in both eyes, but the dog is not blind and is observed to navigate new environments and get around without issue.

Please check with your vet if you should have any questions or concerns about these conditions, and discuss any concerns you may have with your SOS Adoption Counselor.

Adoption Fee: $585

To apply for this dog, fill out an adoption application on our website: www.sosarl.org/aa/

**Additional info you should know - For most of our dogs, we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each of our dogs as an individual and do our best to describe and place them based on personality not breed label. Some dogs may not yet be in New England, nor ready for immediate adoption. There may be additional vetting, quarantine, waiting periods and/or fees depending upon your state of residence. If you have questions or concerns on any of this, you can discuss this with your Adoption Counselor.

animal.description:
Meet MAX.... He is a 5 year old Jack Russel/Wired hair terrier mix boy, 18 lbs, who was surrendered to us because the new wife of the previous owner didn't want dogs in the house and so they got kicked out in a dirt pen in the yard. Max got surrendered with his female companion Maggie. They are very bonded but due to the fact that they are very scared of everything new they are depending so much on each other that in their case it can be a hold back for them to get out of their comfort zone and explore new things.
Means it would be not a terrible thing to break them up and adopt them out separate but they are also available as a pair.

Maggie is the more outgoing one of the two while Max is her follower.

Maggie is a Jack Russel Terrier, also 5 years old, 16 lbs.
Max is currently going through his heartworm treatment, which is fully taken care of by our organization. No side effects are expected and it will not hinder him from a happy and active life.

Both of them have no leash experience and we are looking for a home with a fenced in yard. The reason why is they won't go outside to potty if their only chance to go outside is on a leash which is frightening to them. So one step at the time and there can not be an exception made.

They are crate trained and have no potty accidents in a crate. Both love to snuggle and are very sweet and gentle dogs.
We don't know how they are with cats, potentially great but they are very intimidated by other dogs but will adjust and come around. 
We are looking for a home with no small children. They do very well with small children but younger active and loud children might make them nervous and intimidated. Older Children 10+ will be best.

Those two are amazing they are just very sad and heartbroken and in need of a real and loving home.

If you would like to meet Max and his friend Maggie or just one of them, please send us a message in order to receive an application. We are only able to meet with approved applicants by appointment.

Our adoption fee is $ 350 which includes all vaccines, heartworm test ( treatment), spay and neuter and micro chip. We of course offer a discounted adoption fee if they get adopted as a pair.

animal.description: Daisy is a 10 year old chihuahua who just wants to be loved.  She is a bit grouchy and can be snippy when she first meets you but just needs a chance to get to know you a bit.  Once she does, she loves sitting in your lap and being petted and cuddled.  She also really loves her pink toy and treats!  She was brought to PAWS with two other dogs because mom had to move and couldn't take them with her.  Daisy was very afraid and confused but soon began to see that this was a pretty cool place to be while waiting for her new forever home.  She is about 10 lbs and is black, grey and white.  She is believed to have been born around 12/17/2010.  She is spayed, microchipped, dewormed, current on her rabies and parvo/distemper shots, Heartworm negative and on preventative.  If you have a nice quiet home with no children and not a lot of traffic in and out, Daisy is the perfect girl for you.  Just know that she doesn't always present well or make a good first impression but if you have patience and love, she is a wonderful little girl who will make your life complete!  Her adoption fee is $200.00.

animal.description: Suki is a sweet girl who was found as a stray and was more than happy to spend the night in her finder's home before coming to PACC. Her finder tells us she was gentle, crate-trained and played with the other dogs in the house. We're also told that Suki is a sweetheart-snuggler who loves riding in the car, playing ball and knows sit and shake. Since arriving at PACC, Suki has been a little bit nervous, but staffers say she's a very sweet girl. In play group, Suki was shy at first, but quickly initiated play with other pups. Staffers say she's a very social and tolerant player. She's easy to leash up, walks well and enjoys treats. In play group, she got along well with other dogs, but she's not a fan of the littles. For that reason, we recommend a home free from small dogs. We're sure Suki would love to get out of the shelter and into a home. If she seems like the girl for you, make an appointment and meet her today.

animal.description:
Meet Miss Maggie.... She is a 5 year old Jack Russel female, 16 lbs who was surrendered to us because the new wife of the previous owner didn't want dogs in the house and so they got kicked out in a dirt pen in the yard. Maggie got surrendered with her male companion Max. They are very bonded but due to the fact that they are very scared of everything new they are depending so much on each other that in their case it can be a hold back for them to get out of their comfort zone and explore new things.
Means it would be not a terrible thing to break them up and adopt them out separate but they are also available as a pair.

Maggie is the more outgoing one of the two while Max is her follower.

Max is a terrier mix, also 5 years old, 18 lbs and is currently going through his heartworm treatment.

Both of them have no leash experience and we are looking for a home with a fenced in yard. The reason why is they won't go outside to potty if their only chance to go outside is on a leash which is frightening to them. So one step at the time and there can not be an exception made.

They are crate trained and have no potty accidents in a crate. Both love to snuggle and are very sweet and gentle dogs.
We don't know how they are with cats, potentially great but they are very intimidated by other dogs but will adjust and come around. 
We are looking for a home with no small children. They do very well with small children but younger active and loud children might make them nervous and intimidated. Older Children 10+ will be best.

Those two are amazing they are just very sad and heartbroken and in need of a real and loving home.

If you would like to meet Maggie and her buddy Max or just one of them, please send us a message in order to receive an application. We are only able to meet with approved applicants by appointment.

Our adoption fee is $ 350 which includes all vaccines, heartworm test ( treatment), spay and neuter and micro chip. We of course offer a discounted adoption fee if they get adopted as a pair.

animal.description:
Moxie(formerly Pandora) is an approximately five year old female chihuahua/pomeranian mix and weighs about 10 pounds. She is extremely sweet and likes to be with you whenever possible. Moxie sleeps quietly in her kennel at night and is potty trained as long as she is let out regularly. Moxie likes other dogs and people but takes a minute to warm up as she is shy. She does tend to bond faster and stronger with women than men.

She walks very nicely on a leash and is fairly quiet unless someone comes to the door. Consistency and general soft training and exposure are things that will really help this girl come out of her shell. Professional training is recommended, and some is included in her adoption fee. No small children due to her size and fearfulness. Moxie is currently located in the Kansas City area and it would be great if the adopter could be located in the area so multiples meetings could be set up with Moxie prior to going home with her new family. Moxie first came to us pregnant and was returned due to not bonding with her male adopter(no harsh words, this was a hard decision and was best for Moxie). She will take patience in her new home. Moxie is UTD on vacc., microchipped, and spayed. To apply to adopt visit www.handsofhoperescue.com/adoptapp.
Moxie
's adoption fee is $250. All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. This dog is fostered in Kansas City, KS and adopter must drive to pick up. We do not ship or deliver. We do allow out of state adoptions, however qualified in state applications will be given preference. Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. To learn about Hands of Hope Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at HandsofHopeRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
Junior is a 5 year old male pitty who lives his days appreciating everything and everyone!!
He was found huddled under a dryer vent for warmth on 12/6/20. He’s very lucky to be alive as he was almost facing hypothermia. Thanks to the quick action of concerned citizens and immediate vet care that’s just a memory now.
 (We believe him to have been tied outside and neglected for quite some time before he escaped that lucky day)
He is a super sweet and affectionate over sized lap dog who would prefer a home where humans are generally always with him. After a taste of love, care and attention he can become anxious alone after being alone and forgotten. Junior needs to be the ONLY animal in the house as he's not good with other dogs and wouldn't be good with cats. He loves chewing on his chewy bones. Junior also knows how to sit and give paw with both paws.  
His adoption fee is $150.00 which includes being up to date on vaccinations including rabies, microchipped, dewormed, on flea/tick preventative and neutered.
We are a FOSTER based dog rescue therefore there isn't one central location with open hours to see our available dogs. They are all in loving foster homes enjoying learning how to be a furry family member. If interested we only set up meet and greets AFTER approving adoption applications with interested adopters as to not waste anyone's time.
All current/past pets MUST be up kept to date on vaccinations as well as being spayed/neutered to adopt from our rescue.
