IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING LILLY OR ANY OF OUR OTHER BABIES, YOU MUST HAVE A COMPLETED APPLICATION.  YOU CAN FIND THE APPLICATION BY TYPING IN THE FOLLOWING ADDRESS:
                                  https://www.pawspaws.org
The application is under Forms.  I will arrange meet and greets after I have approved the application.  Thanks for your interest and cooperation.

Lilly has seen a lot in her less than two years of life.  She has had two litters of puppies already and was never loved and cuddled like she should have been.  When she first arrived, she was terribly afraid and would just try desperately to avoid any contact.  She was not a biter but would just try to melt into the wall to try to get away.  But after a few days of lots of patience and love, she began to see that being loved and cuddled was a pretty cool thing!  She has come a long way but still has a ways to go before she will fully trust and not be afraid.  She is funny and sweet and loves to play with the other dogs her size.  She loves her treats and, once she is in your arms, she loves being petted and snuggled.  She will need a quiet home with no children and no dogs larger than her.  She is looking for a home where someone will have the time and patience to continue to show her how good life can be.  She weighs 6 lbs and was born 05/02/2019.  What a treasure this baby is!  Her adoption fee is $350.

animal.description:
Stanley is as cute as they come, but he is a bit of a problematic dog, so will only be adopted into a home that understands chihuahua's and is an experienced dog owner.

12 pound Stanley will be best suited in an area that isn't dense in dogs, as he is quite reactive to other dogs he sees and meets.  He's young still, only 2 years old, so we're confident with an experienced handler and support from a professional trainer, Stanley can overcome his insecurities.  

Stanley originally came from Texas through another rescue.  He was adopted to a woman that was not dog experienced, and Stanley was a lot of dog for someone without the knowledge of handling reactive, anxious dogs.  With the lockdown, professional training support was a struggle and the adopter opted to surrender to Mattie's Place.  It was a heart wrenching decision, as she fell hopelessly in love with this boy, but the burden of care was too much with the behaviour issues Stanley came with.

Stanley has been bounced around quite a bit before arriving to Mattie's Place and along with that, has been given multiple names.  There's just been no consistency in this boys life and it's time we bring that to a halt and give him what he needs for stability, so he can learn to trust and grow and be the best version of himself.

Stanley is also very set in his ways, and will not hesitate to snap or bite if he feels you're doing something he does not approve of, such as putting on a harness, or picking him up when he's not in the mood.  He's a small dog with a lot of anxiety right now and will need time and patience to work through his insecurities, that may exist for months or years to come.

He's a feisty boy, without a doubt, but he's also incredibly loving, cuddly, loyal and an all around good boy, when he feels safe and secure.

Stanley's adopter will need to have incredible patience and loads of compassion.  He also does better with women than men, so a female adopter is preferable. 

Because he's a bit of a jerk, no kids or regularly visiting kids, under 15 years old in the home.

Stanley's adopter is a female in a quiet home, that works from home (he does have separation anxiety) and doesn't have a lot of people coming and going.  Ad adopter that can put energy into helping an insecure dog become more confident and work with a professional trainer to help him overcome his areas of weakness.  You'll be rewarded with the most loyal companion you could hope to meet.

MEDICAL: 

Right Hind Leg -- Stifle deformed -- Old injury [doesn't bother him at all, will be considered pre-existing for any future issues should they arise, with insurance]

Deciduous Tooth extractions - baby teeth that never pushed out with the incoming adult teeth.  We will have these removed, at the expense of Mattie's Place, January 27th at our rescue veterinarian.

FROM HIS FOSTER MOM:

It took Stanley a couple of days to settle in.  But once he got there, he transformed from a sad and angry dog into a high-energy and affectionate sweetie.  

Stanley is still very young, he loves to play and is very curious, he still has lots to learn.  

He’s also a small guy but with a big personality.  

If things don’t go his way he will make sure you know; if he wants to cuddle but your aren’t available, he will walk around the house and whine, if he wants to play but you’re busy, he will make noises with his squeaky toy.  

____________________________________________

As of today, though our protocols could change tomorrow, we are still moving forward with adoptions. Our process has changed from some of the previous elements: We are a registered animal welfare organization, so we are deemed an essential service.

All paperwork completed online, video home visits, meet and greets outside respecting social distancing, leashes/collars/supplies wiped down and disinfected (GermiCide 3 wipes), disinfectant on the dog prior to handoff (Aqueos wipes for dogs)

-----------------------

To note: the above description is relevant to this dog in his current setting. Home changes & adopter personalities can bring out different behaviours not previously seen.

We do not specifically kid/cat test our dogs when they arrive at Mattie's Place. That just wouldn't be fair to the dog or child/cat.

We also do not claim, endorse, suggest or hint at, that any of our dogs are hypoallergenic, low shed or no-shed.

Adoption fee includes: spay/neuter, deworming, defleaing, vaccinations, nose to tail health exam, leash|collar, 6 months of preventative based on season/need, DNA test for entertainment purposes, dishes, poop bags, food and any extras she has accumulated in foster care.

animal.description:
They say to ask for what you need so here goes, I need a man and a job! I LOVE a good man and I thrive on working. 
When I was pregnant I was picked up by animal control and placed in a shelter. No one came to claim me. I delivered three puppies in that shelter, two of which did not survive. I was rescued from that shelter with my baby boy Solo and we moved to Colorado to start a new life. My son found a loving home and I'm looking to do the same. I am a loving momma and aunt. I enjoy running and playing with other dogs. I also LOVE running with my foster dad! 

My foster parents say that I am a smart beautiful American Staffordshire Terrier mix. who enjoys playing fetch and at the end of the day snuggling on the couch. I believe I'm a lap dog, even though they tell me that my 60 pounds takes up a lot of lap. If there's a couch and a movie going, count me in! I would love to explore more of Colorado either by hiking or jogging. 

I am up to date with my vaccinations, wormed, microchipped, and spayed. I am also heart worm negative. My adoption fee is $300.

Due to my breed mix, I am unable to live in cities and rentals who dissallow bully breeds. 

If you are interested in meeting me and live in an area/situation where bully breeds are allowed, please visit the following website to complete an online application, www.innocentpawspuppyrescue.org

animal.description:
FROM THE FOSTER: Radar is an awesome dog who loves snuggles, walks, and naps. He knows basic tricks and is great in the house. He prefers to spend his days inside with his humans and would make a wonderful work-from-home companion, but he can also be left at home for a full workday without incident. Though he can be playful, his energy level is lower than the average lab. He gets along well with most other dogs, especially if they are easy-going and enjoy playing!

FROM THE FOSTER: Radar is great in the car, great with my senior dog and another friends dog that was dropped off for the weekend. He LOVES the yard. Has tried to get on the furniture to get some attention. Its Obvious that he has been in a home with rules that were enforced as he listens and obeys when you call him back into the house and knows, sit, shake and down. He is house trained and working on leaving him alone for short periods and so far so good. Hes an awesome dog!.

ORIGINAL POST: Radar is a five (5) year old, 65 pound lab mix that was surrendered to the shelter. He is appropriately named as his one ear that pops up makes him look like he is listening in on everything. Hes in our pack in boarding now and doing well with the other dogs. He is athletic and strong, so he would do well with an owner who is the same. If you would like to foster to adopt Radar, please go to www.atlantalabrescue.com to fill on application or email an inquiry.

animal.description: Lucky is a two (2) year old, 105 pound lab mix that was surrendered by his owner to the vet clinic because they didnt have time for him. What gave that away was the fact that when he came in for a checkup, they found that his collar had grown into his neck and they had to get bolt cutters to get it off. Several weeks later he came back to the vet for another visit and they found the bandages had grown into his neck. Luckily, this happy boy is not too worse for the wear and now that we have him, his chances for the life he deserves just got better. He is in boarding and in daycare. Although hes a big boy he is a little shy with people at first. Hes good with other dogs, but sometimes acts like he knows he is bigger than the rest, so he would probably be best in the home with a female dog. If you would like to foster to adopt this beautiful boy, please go to www.atlantalabrescue.com to fill out an application.

animal.description:
NOTE: Cooper is still in the south and not here for you to meet. He will most likely be adopted sight unseen without having a chance to be fostered up here. If you are comfortable with this type of adoption, the first step is to submit an application. Please read all about our wonderful rescue and submit an application at at www.foreverhomerescue.org

Adoption coordinator Kathy 

Look at that polka dotted nose! This is Cooper. He is 1 yr old and weighs about 48 lbs. He was born to a stray mom. He has medium energy and will make a great walking Buddy. He likes playing with other dogs, being pet, and treats. He’s shy at first, but loving once he gets to know you. He needs someone who will be patient with him and give him time to settle in. He’s crate and house trained and doing well learning how to walk on a leash. He is still young, and will chew so needs to be crated when left alone. He’s a beautiful young dog that will do great in an active home that has the time and patience to provide training and socialization so he be the best dog he can be. He is not a good match for the city or an apartment. Preference will be given to applicants with an enclosed fence. He hasn’t been cat tested. Adoption fee $400. 



Please complete an online APPLICATION if you wish to adopt.  Forever Home Rescue New England is a 501(c)3  non-profit organization. We are a network of foster homes in the South and the New England area. THERE IS NO SPECIFIC SHELTER LOCATION. If you wish to meet our dogs, you must first be approved by going through our application and screening process. Forever Home Rescue suggests obedience training for all puppies and dogs. All dogs are up to date on their shots, dewormed and spayed or neutered. Vet fees, transport fee and New England quarantine fees ARE INCLUDED in each dog's adoption fee. Also, any dogs older than pups--even if they are not marked housetrained in their posting---usually housetrain within a day or two, because most are used to living outside in the south and will prefer to do their business outdoors. Our dogs and pups are best suited for families with children 5 yrs old and up. If you are approved to adopt, please submit the $100 deposit by clicking on our rescue's name in this posting (Forever Home Rescue New England--in purple) which will bring you to a new page with the deposit link at the bottom.  STOP! If you have not been notified of your approval status do not make a deposit.

animal.description:
NOTE: THIS IS A COURTESY POSTING ONLY!
THIS PET IS NOT AVAILABLE THROUGH BROTHER WOLF ANIMAL RESCUE. 
PLEASE CONTACT THE OWNER FOR MORE INFORMATION OR TO MAKE AN APPLICATION FOR ADOPTION. 

The owner's email is: cleomoreandmoore@gmail.com

Ripley is a cuddly, affectionate, much loved, energetic girl in
excellent health. She was adopted from a shelter 9 months ago, and has
become a well-behaved dog since then. She is crate trained, walks on
the leash without pulling, and doesn't chew things up. She loves
hikes, going swimming, and playing with other dogs. She loves
everyone, which is wonderful! She was very scared in the shelter, and
was terrified of people when we first met us, but now she's pretty
fearless. Ripley has lived in a house with cats, and we think she's
okay with them, but she's exuberant so cats aren't okay with her.
Ripley loves other dogs, and does well with calm yet playful dogs. She
has a lot of energy and can overwhelm some of her friends. She loves
to snuggle with her humans, enjoys her chew toys and playing tug. She
eats well but isn't food obsessed. She has really blossomed in the
last 9 months, and would make an amazing companion for someone active
and experienced with pit bull terriers. Her owner had sudden health
problems and can't care for her, so I am helping to find a good home.
We travel between the Carrboro/Chapel Hill area, and Asheville. If you
sound like a good match, I'm happy to travel to either area.
She is 45 lbs, spayed, and up to date on her vaccinations.

Please call or email with any questions you might have about this sweet girl!

animal.description: ***SPECIAL NEEDS*** Diesel will be at the shelter 1/29 and 1/30 for visits, after this he will be going back with his foster, please call for more information or to set up a meet/greet. Diesel is an amazing dog. Loves people, males and females. Enjoys kids. Hardly barks and loves dog walks. He likes to play ball and chase it, he likes to be brushed and doesn't mind being bathed. Diesel did very well in foster for the holidays. We are considering Diesel as special needs with his thyroid condition that will require further follow up with the adopters veterinarian. This is a life long medical issue that will need to be maintained. Our shelter veterinarian has reached a point where she feels Diesel needs an adopter that can find Diesel his own veterinarian to take over care his care. Diesel has a zest for life and so much to offer his people. This guy has done a complete 180! Arriving at the shelter with terrible skin, an out of control untreated thyroid issue, so uncomfortable he didn't want to get up and depressed to the point of not eating. To see him now is amazing! Don't miss out on meeting this sweet face.

animal.description:
Lucas is a 1-2 year old, siberian husky. He has all the traditional husky traits and is a very affectionate boy. Lucas is a tripod, so he will require a home with little to no stairs. In addition, because traditional leash-walking isn't the best way for him to get his exercise, he will also require a home with a six-foot, secure (husky secure) fence.
Lucas gets along well with dogs his size and also loves people. He does not, as is normal with this breed, like cats. He should not be in a home with them and, preferably, small dogs.
If you are interested in learning more about Lucas, please email his foster mom, bjames@westga.edu. She can provide you with much more specific information about the home that is best for him and walk you through the adoption process.
Only those with breed experience should apply. He is fully vetted and microchipped, and his adoption fee is $500.

animal.description:
Daisy Duke is a female Labrador mix puppy who was born around November 30, 2020. She came to Prairie Paws Rescue with her two siblings. Mom is a Yellow Labrador and unsure who the dad is.
They are named after the Dukes of Hazard TV show (Luke, Bo and Daisy Duke).
Puppies are lots of fun and also lots of work. Daisy Duke will need a family who is willing to work with her on house training, socializing, and helping reach full potential of being part of a family.
Daisy Duke will be adopted as an indoor family member.  A Puppy outside this time of year is cruel in the North Dakota elements. 
She will be adopted with age appropriate medical work and go to his new home with a spay contract.
Shots, worming flea treatment rabies shot micro chip and vet exam completed prior to adoption. 
Adopting fee is $150 + tax with an approved application.  Adoption Application is available on the website www.prairiepawsrescue.com and go to the adopt link to download the jotform application fill it out and submit. 
Prairie Paws Rescue does not adopt on a first come basis but who will provide the best home suited to the pets needs

He will be adopted with age appropriate medical work and go to his new home with a neuter contract.
Shots, worming flea treatment rabies shot micro chip and vet exam completed prior to adoption.

animal.description:
MUST BE IN THE STL, METRO IL AREA TO HE CONSIDERED FOR ADOPTION!

Bug’s story... for reasons unknown Bug was surrendered to an out of area rescue in early 2019. She was adopted in September 2019 to a local family. Because of her skittish  nature, the family lost her on the same day of adoption. Bug was missing for over a year. 

In December 2020 we saw a social media post about a dog that had been living in a horse pasture and had taken up shelter in a den type brush pile. The dog was extremely skittish and would not go to anyone. FAHR was asked to help and within two days we were able to trap her. The dog was scanned for a microchip and the chip was registered to Bug. We couldn’t believe that Bug was still alive and had traveled 20+ miles. 

Since trapping Bug she has been in a foster home learning how to acclimate to life indoors and learning how to trust humans. Bug is a very shy and skittish girl.  After being in foster for nearly two months she has moments of being confident but will quickly revert back to being shy and scared. She is happy and manageable most of the time but when she gets scared she will keep her distance. 

Bug is a mini aussie, six years old and is house and kennel trained. The perfect family would be someone who has the understanding and patience needed to acclimate a shy and skittish dog to a new environment. We prefer Bug have a tall, secure privacy fence and must have another dog(s) in the home that is confident and can show her the way. Bug may do well with older kids or teens but feel young kids and toddlers may be too overwhelming for her. She is house and kennel trained and loves being with her pack of furry foster siblings. 

Bug’s adoption fee is $300. This includes spay, vaccinations, microchip, dewormer and maintaining heartworm prevention while in our care.

If you would like to be selected for a meeting with our girl, please submit an online adoption application by copying the link below into your browser. 

https://form.jotformpro.com/50153632350949

animal.description:
NOTE:  The mailbox petfinder sends the "Ask About" email inquiries to is not as closely monitored as the email address applications go to.   That feature is a default with petfinder, and is not a part of our adoption process.

The first step in our adoption process is the application.  Completed applications take priority over inquiries.  To apply to adopt, please copy and paste the following url:

https://fs30.formsite.com/legacygsd/form4/index.html

Introducing Possum.  This cutie-patootie is a Peke/Schipperke mix.  He's around 7-8 yrs old and weighs 12lbs. 

Possum is blind from early onset cataracts. It doesn't slow him down one bit! He can navigate the house and yard with ease.  He's good with other dogs.  He's got 4 little canine buddies he likes to go outside with. He's fine with dog savvy cats.  If they don't mess with him he doesn't mess with them.  

When Possum arrived at the shelter he was naked. With medicated baths and melatonin he fluffed right up. All except his tail.  It's naked with the exception of a few wild random hairs.  Hence the name Possum.  He's got a little curly possum tail. 

Possum is the sweetest boy!  He loves to be held and loved on.  He's a cuddle bug and enjoys lots of TLC from his people.  He is crate trained and does pretty well in the house when taken out regularly.  Possum would do best in a home with a fenced yard.  He doesn't really care for a leash. Having a yard that is familiar is best because he'll learn to navigate it with ease.  Possum is currently in an adult home and would do best in an adult home or home with children 12yr and over. 

Other than being blind and having a naked tail Possum is in good health. He's neutered, is vaccinated, tested for heartworms and 5 diseases spread by ticks,  is microchipped and on monthly heartworm and flea prevention.

As with all of our dogs, we recommend a basic obedience class to help him understand what is expected of him, and this also helps with the bonding process. 

Possum’s adoption fee is $475, which covers all his vetting, preventatives, fostering costs and other associated expenses.  We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21.

animal.description:
Meet this sweetie named Minnie! She came into the shelter mid January 2021 and is patiently awaiting her chance at a loving home. She is 4 years old, current on shots, and just a sweetheart. She loves playing with toys and soaking up body rubs and affection. Maybe you have the most amazing loving FOREVER home for sweet Minnie?! Stop by for a visit with this pretty girl and give her a fabulous life with you! 
If you have another dog and are interested in meeting another potential new furry member please bring him or her to the shelter and meet on neutral ground before adopting. No need to shuffle the animals around any more than necessary. Please know that 1 mosquito bite can create heart worms and they can be fatal if not treated. It is VERY important to keep your pets healthy and protected by keeping them on a once a month heart worm and flea/tick prevention. These animals are counting on you as their owner to provide them with lots a love and the proper health care so PLEASE make sure you are aware and prepared before adopting. Owning a pet is an extra expense and responsibility but is so worth every minute and penny you invest in them. They will add lots of joy and unconditional love if given a fair chance.
The shelter is open Mon.-Fri. 10-1, 2-5 and Sat. 10-4. Adopt a homeless pet and save a life. If you can not adopt right now come out and volunteer and make a difference in the lives of these animals while they await their FOREVER home.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet DUFFY! Duffy is a sweet and friendly Great Pyrenees mix. He has double dews. He is a year old and weighs 65 pounds but needs to gain about 10 pounds. He is very calm and quiet in the house. He loves people and seeks attention. He will sit in front of you, offer his "Pyr paw," and try to crawl onto your lap for pets and cuddles! Duffy was a stray. He is an escape artist and needs a securely fenced yard. He would also do well in a condo or townhome. Duffy is learning how to be a family dog. He does not take treats from hands (although he loves his food) and does not know what to do with toys. Duffy did well with his bath and was perfect for his pedicure. He offered his paws to the groomer and enjoyed the attention! Duffy is reliably house-trained. He sleeps and eats baby-gated in a small room. He has nice house manners and will likely do well loose in the house. He does not beg at the table or chew inappropriately. Duffy knows "sit" and "shake." He walks very well on leash and rides well in the car. He gets along with dogs of as long as they don't get in his face. He can live in a home with or without other dogs. This sweetie is ready for his forever family! Duffy is currently in Texas but can be on the next NW transport.

All our dogs require secure VISIBLE fencing. All current pets in adoptive home must be spayed/neutered and up to date on vaccinations.

Please note: RAGOM’s adoption territory includes: Minnesota; Iowa; North Dakota; South Dakota; Western Wisconsin (within 75 miles of the Minnesota border). We are not taking out of territory inquiries at this time.

Bandit was rescued from an auction of breeding dogs. He is learning to overcome his fear of humans and will need a medium to large, confident dog in his forever home as a mentor as well as a playmate. Bandit can live with cats. A physical fence is required to keep him safe, and any children in the home must be at least 13. 

Bandit's foster mom stated:
Bandit has taken more baby steps. The most exciting is that he will come during the early morning hours while I am still in bed and let me scratch his chest and rub his face! It is a thrill every morning now as he leans into my hand for more.

I could lay there for hours if my residents weren't so persistent in trying to get me up. Of course, when I do start to get up, he runs back to his safe dog bed in the bedroom and waits. He won't let me pet him for that long anywhere else.

Bandit has also started taking treats from friends that visit outdoors. I have two friends that he has seen several times-in our pod. Check out the video where he takes a treat from my friend Jill even as she is standing up!

So I am not without hope for Mr Bandit. Hope that he will find his forever family, hope that he will allow the morning love to spread to other parts of the day. 

If you have another medium to large dog, a fence, patience, and most of all good experience with extremely fearful dogs, please consider this sweet boy.

To learn more about Bandit, see his bio at: https://ragom.org/dogs/bandit-20-043a

animal.description:
Meet this handsome fella named MHKai! He came into the shelter mid January 2021 and is ready for his “real” FOREVER home. He is 1 year 5 months old, current on shots, already neutered, and just a happy playful young fella who is excited to meet his new person or family.  Maybe you have the most amazing loving home for this charming fella?! Stop by the shelter for a visit with MHKai today and adopt him into your heart and home! 
If you have another dog and are interested in meeting another potential new furry member please bring him or her to the shelter and meet on neutral ground before adopting. No need to shuffle the animals around any more than necessary. Please know that 1 mosquito bite can create heart worms and they can be fatal if not treated. It is VERY important to keep your pets healthy and protected by keeping them on a once a month heart worm and flea/tick prevention. These animals are counting on you as their owner to provide them with lots a love and the proper health care so PLEASE make sure you are aware and prepared before adopting. Owning a pet is an extra expense and responsibility but is so worth every minute and penny you invest in them. They will add lots of joy and unconditional love if given a fair chance.
The shelter is open Mon.-Fri. 10-1, 2-5 and Sat. 10-4. Adopt a homeless pet and save a life. If you can not adopt right now come out and volunteer and make a difference in the lives of these animals while they await their FOREVER home.

animal.description:
Meet Beefcake!

Hi, I'm Beefcake. I'm 6 years old, 60 pounds, and I love you so much! I know we haven't met yet, but trust me. I love you. I love everything! I'd love to have a home with other bigger dogs to play with. I'm a five-star player, and chasing another dog around the yard would be the best! But if you don't have any siblings for me, that's okay. I really like going to the dog park, meeting new friends on walks and the company of humans just fine. I could live with older kids, but since I'm a bigger guy, and I get a bit excited easily, younger, small kids I might knock over. My favorite toys are ropes for tug-o-war, anything that squeaks and good, old-fashioned sticks. I'm the goodest boy and don't have accidents in the house, but my foster mom still kennels me when she's gone because I think everything is a toy. My foster mom says I'm good on a leash, and I have the energy and fitness to keep up on jogs, hikes and nice, long walks. I tend to chase critters and pull to meet new dog friends, but I'm just being friendly! I listen when you say it's time to move on. At home, I'm the most loving pup. I love to curl up for a tv binge session, sit beside you while you work, or cuddle next to you for a nap. The more we overlap, the better! If you're looking for a new best friend or biggest fan, look no further. I'm your guy!

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

Isn't Lubby the cutest!

If you are interested in Lubby, fill out an application at
www.fayettehumane.org/adopt/dogapplication

Due to COVID-19, we are not able to facilitate meet and greets until a family is approved and then only at the foster family's discretion. At this time, we are not holding dog adoptions at Petsmart.

**Applications can take anywhere from 5-7 business days to complete. animal.description:
Meet Ernst! 

Mr Ernst is an approximately 10 year old, 17 pound Shih Tzu. He has the cutest face and rocks his snaggletooth. Mr. Ernst just loves to be by his people; he is great with adults and older kids. His very favorite thing is belly rubs. When you first meet him he will likely roll right over to ask for those belly scratches. His second favorite thing is naps - he's a pro and even likes cuddling in bed at night with his humans. He does great on car rides too! Ernst gets along with both large and small dogs, but only if they are laid back like he is - he gets grumpy if a dog is too much in his personal space, and prefers to eat by himself. He gets very excited about cats, so would do best in a home without them. He is not perfectly potty trained; although he goes potty every time you let him outside, he will sometimes lift a leg inside as well. He has no problem wearing a belly band, which completely solves that issue. Unfortunately Ernst has a grade 5/6 heart murmur and has been diagnosed with "mitral valve insufficiency". He is currently taking two medications at a total cost of about $50 per month to help his heart work better. The good news is he is not showing any outward symptoms of this. He will need another echocardiogram in 6 months to see how things are going. All Ernst wants is someone to give him love, care, and belly scratches in his golden years. Could it be you?

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

animal.description:
Click my picture for more info. on me!
Meet Orla!

Orla is looking for her forever home! She is a one year old German Shepherd mix who loves to play, play, play! She loves other medium to larger breed dogs who will play with her, but she can be quite vocal when she first meets strangers. She has not figured out that BARK BARK BARK is not the best way to greet new friends. She loves to wrestle and would love a home with someone (dog or human) who will play with her. However, the greeting does not extend to cats- she LOVES to chase cats!

She came to us a few months ago after being hit by a car and limping on her broken lower leg for days. A few months of splints, many many X-rays, and lots of rest, and she's really to find her forever home. Orla has been a trooper throughout and has loved everyone she has met! Because of her prey drive, we think that a fenced in yard is needed. She has already had one accident in her life and does not need another!

Orla is a very loyal girl and will follow you everywhere you go. She is sweet and gentle, but she can get rambunctious while playing. She ADORES belly rubs and will flop down into your lap for one. Personal space? Noooo! That's not a thing! She will pick up her leash and walk with it to the door to tell you when she wants to go out. Orla us almost housetrained and has only had a few accidents.

If you are interested in her, fill out an application at

Meet Milo!!!  Are you looking for a party boy??  If so, Milo is the one for you!!!  Milo gets very excited about playing with other dogs, and meeting new people.  He will need a fenced yard and a if you have a dog who loves to play back, then Milo would love that.  He will do best with a very active family.  

Milo would love to go to doggie training, to learn how to not jump.  He wants to learn the manners to be the best boy he can be.  He is always happy and full of life.  He wants to learn and we feel it will be fairly easy as he is food motivated.  Once its time to settle down at night, Milo will snuggle up you.

If you are active, go running, hiking, camping, anything fun and exciting, Milo will be ready to go with you.  Don't miss out on this awesome boy!!!

If interested in Milo, please email to inquire at: SCREENING.FETCHINGHEARTS@GMAIL.COM OR COPY LINK BELOW TO APPLY AND FILL OUT AN APPLICATION: https://www.fetchingheartsrescue.org/adoption-form-online to fill out an application.

Unless otherwise indicated, all dogs adopted through Fetching Hearts have received the following before being available for adoption:

Thorough veterinary examination

All routine annual vaccinations, including Rabies, DHLPP, Bordatella (Kennel Cough), Heartworm Test, Fecal Test, Deworming, Microchip, Flea and Tick Prevention and Heartworm Prevention.

Spay/Neuter
All dogs are quarantined for two weeks outside of the shelter (puppies four weeks) to ensure they don't break with disease.

VETTING NOTE: Fetching Hearts Rescue completely vets our dogs thoroughly to the best of our knowledge based on communication with our Southern Vets. If anything is brought to our attention, we treat the dog. After adopting the dog, you will be responsible for following up with all vetting going forward.

HEARTWORM NOTE: Dogs who were treated for Heartworm can test positive up to 4-6 months after last treatment. All dogs are immediately put on Heartguard/Ivermectin following the treatment to kill the Heartworm larvae. All dogs should be re-tested after 5-6 months from the last Heartworm treatment.

animal.description:
Rosie Mamma is a very energetic dog who loves nothing more than a good ball! She will play with any kind, from tennis balls to soccer balls and anything in between. She seems to prefer something a bit oversized so she can chase and paw at it, but she won't complain about a regular size ball. Rosie loves to fetch, and when she needs a break she will flop into the grass for a chew or a tummy rub. She is very strong and will need to work on her leash manners. She enjoys treats, but nothing beats out her toys. Rosie's previous owners said she was dog selective, but we believe she would be best as the only dog based on her introductions here. She does attend playgroup, but she would prefer to have her home to herself because she does require supervision and management. She has shown a lot of interest in cats and small animals, so she would be best as the only animal. Rosie has lived with children twice and likes them very much! 

Rosie is a part of our Sit, Stay, Adopt! program due to some behavioral challenges. She is fearful/reactive to strangers, especially men, and will need behavior modification training to work on this. At the shelter, she is working on wearing a basket muzzle, appropriate engagement, and positive reinforcement of appropriate behaviors. She will take a dedicated owner and a special home to succeed, but we know that her person is out there! Our behavior consultant will arrange for meetings with interested adopters to help Rosie get comfortable and find her forever home.

Hudson is a strikingly handsome White English Setter who traveled here from Turkey after one of our rescuers found him in a local shelter. Being an English Setter, Hudson  prances and stands with great elegance. He ADORES EVERYONE, children and people young and old and greets all with an enthusiastic smile and snuggles. Hudson is a 3 year old neutered male who gets along well with other dogs and cats and shows zero aggression. His sweet, loving, joyful nature is a pleasure to be around. He does have energy and would do best in a home with a yard to play in and a few long walks a day. Hudson is currently being fostered in a home with another young dog and enjoys playtime with his foster brother. Therefore, we are looking for a home for Hudson with another playful dog. 

Hudson is also being fostered in a home with cats and gets along flawlessly with them. He is potty trained and shows no bad habits of barking or chewing and is crate trained as well although he’s just as happy to sleep in your bed to snuggle! Although Hudson has not had any accidents in his foster home..he will need gentle reminders of the proper place to go in his new home. 

 Hudson is still learning basic obedience skills and is gaining ground on sit, stay, down and come but does pull on the leash unless walked with a harness or gentle leader. He’s an eager learner however and very treat motivated. He also enjoys car rides A LOT and would be happy to join you on any journeys. Will the next step of his journey be with you?

Please note: Hudson is being fostered in San Diego, CA. Due to the high cost of travel, Hudson’s adoption fee is $1,000. 

If you are interested in making Hudson a part of your family, please head over to our website www.roversretreat.org to fill out an adoption application.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email Dena at DenaE@k-9lifesavers.org
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Baby Bobby
Estimated Breed: Chihuahua Terrier MIX
Approximate Age: born 10/23/2020
Approximate Weight: 5 LBS
Currently Living at: foster
Adoption Fee: $375
DOG'S DESCRIPTION:
Bobby, one of the Brady Bunch litter, born 10/23 is the climber of the bunch and he is ready for his loving FOREVER home. A puppy is a huge commitment, please be sure you understand and are ready for supporting the puppy needs in time, training, attention, and love. Mom is a Chihuahua (the last pic in the group), daddy is unknown but probably another terrier of some sort. Submit an application, when puppies have adopters they will be removed from the website.
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, rabies (if puppy is old enough), distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing (if puppy is old enough), monthly heartworm prevention while in our care, monthly flea/tick prevention while in our care, and our transport costs. As part of the adoption agreement, adopters agree to get the pup spayed/neutered and provide K-9 Lifesavers with proof of spay/neuter. K-9 Lifesavers does not cover the cost of spay/neuter for puppies 6 months or younger.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Help Save Lives! Make a tax-deductible donation today and help save a life. Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support! We are all volunteer based organization so every cent from your donation goes directly to the dogs in our care.
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Check out our social media! Search for us on Facebook, Twitter, Pinterest and Instagram!!
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!
SPONSOR ME!
Visit: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/

animal.description:
***All animals listed on our website are in private foster homes. To arrange a meet and greet with a dog, you MUST fill out the adoption application so that it can be sent to the foster parent for review to determine if your home is a match for the dog. If a dog receives multiple applications, we operate on a best-fit basis, not first come first served.***

Hi! My name is Huck! I have so much love to give. You can tell 'cause I have a heart on my head! My foster family says I'm kinda weird and goofy. I am easily spooked, and a bit timid. I have been more and more open every day since I got to my foster family's house. I love living with my foster family. They feed me lots of food and snacks (I'm a big fan of treats and meals), and they have other dogs around, too! I love having dog friends around to play with, and people around to scratch my HUGE ears. 

When I'm inside, I am very calm, reserved, and respectful. I mostly lay on my favorite dog bed. In the back yard, I am much more excitable and I love to run around and bark. Don't worry, my bark is actually very cute and endearing. It sounds like a very muted ""whoo!"". I am pretty submissive, and I get along with everybody. My perfect forever home would have some space for me to run around, preferably a fenced-in yard. I would also really love to have another dog around to play with, but I would also be okay with frequent dog park visits. I'm not the type of dog to shower you in affection at first, but in a few short weeks, I will be trying to climb into your lap. 

I am neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations, microchipped, have been dewormed, and am current on my monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventatives. My adoption fee is $300. If you think I could be the one for you, please fill out an adoption application on our website: www.secondchancenc.org. Thank you!

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Honeydew, or Honey for short! I am an 11 year old retriever mix. I am about 60 pounds, but that is a few more pounds than I should be, so my foster family has been helping me try and lose a little weight.

I am currently going through heartworm treatment, so my activity has to be restricted until that is finished. When I wasn't on activity restrictions, I liked walking around the block with my foster family. Since I'm an older girl and a little overweight, my hips bother me just a bit so our walks are just a casual stroll. I have made great improvements since I got here though - when I first got to my foster family's house I wasn't able to make it around the block and I couldn't walk up the stairs of the front porch. Now I can do both!

My foster home has three other dogs, and I get along with them well, but I'm not super playful, I just like to take it easy and sit with my foster mom and dad.

An ideal home for me would be the following:

 Someone who is either an early bird or goes back to sleep easily (if needed)! My current schedule is going to bed around 9 or 10 and waking up between 4 and 5.

 If I'm allowed on the couch and/or in the bed, someone who is able to lift me, at least part of the way. I can get my front legs up on the couch, but I haven't quite mastered the back legs yet.

 A one-story home. I can walk up a couple of stairs if it is a front porch or something, but I can't really do more than that, and I have a little trouble going down the stairs as well.

 Someone who is looking for a dog that is more like a cat. I am kind of a funny girl and I don't really care too much about getting pet or playing. Mostly I just like to be near my foster mom or dad, sometimes snuggled up next to them, but sometimes just being in the same room is sufficient!

 Someone who will help me shed these last few pounds. Once I can start taking walks again I think that will really help.

A few other miscellaneous things about me:

 I am on a couple of medications for arthritis and joint pain that will need to continue.

 I am housetrained!

 My foster mom says I am the funniest dog she knows. I don't know what she means by
that, she just thinks I do funny things I guess!

 I LOVE treats. I know, all dogs love treats, but I really love them. Because of my weight
I get them pretty sparingly, but I get about 10 years younger when it's treat time.

If it sounds like I might be a good fit and you are interested in adopting me, please fill out an application on our website: www.secondchancenc.org. I am so excited to meet you!

Laila Lee has to find her new forever home because her current owners have allergies and also doesn't have the time to dedicate to her.

Adoption Requirements are as such:

The owner is subject to placement outside of our organization. We cannot guarantee availability.

Dogs are tested for heartworm and cats are tested for FeLV/FIV (results negative unless otherwise noted). A tax-deductible adoption fee of $150 is required for adult dogs, puppies are $200, and dogs over the age of 10 are $85. Adult cat adoption fees are $50, kittens under one year are $90, and cats over the age of 10 are $35.

animal.description:
Breed: Mountain Cur mix
Sex: Male
DOB: ~10/12/2020
Weight: 15 lbs
Energy Level: Puppy Energy!
Personality Type: Fun, Social, Outgoing
History: Transferred from another shelter
Good With: Dogs, Cats, Kids
Ideal Home: Any home ready for an active puppy! Apartments may be ok!
Fence Requirements: Preferred
Special Info:

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description: This sweet boy loves people, loves playing and gets along well with other dogs that can handle his energy. He loves to play and will run for hours. He can be a very bossy and pushy boy. He needs an owner who understands his breed and is willing to work out the kinks. Positives- he loves attention and praise. He enjoys ""working"" and will need a job or someone who will be able to engage his busy mind. He is not a backyard, laze around dog. He must have boundaries. Negatives- does not like having his toys taken away during play and has snapped/growled during play time. He is however easily redirected and learns very quickly what it is you want from him. He has an extremely high prey drive that will need to be channeled towards productive work/play. For that reason we are requesting no one with small children at this time. Breed savvy home a must. Fill out an application at www.res-que.org under adoption info.Our dogs are spayed/neutered and utd on shots before adoption unless medically not advised by our Vet.

animal.description: Hey guys, my name is Riley. I'm still very new to FDHS and am still VERY scared. I've had a pretty traumatic couple weeks...my owner and best buddy passed away and I ended up here. I know the people here mean well, but I just shake and bark from my kennel. I know I'll warm up and come out of my shell once I feel safe, and then my true personality will shine through. The humans here have found that I reeeaaally love squeaky toys, even more so than snacks! I'm looking for a quiet, patient home that will take the time to get to know me and let me feel safe and loved. I am around a year old, neutered, vaccinated and heartworm negative.

Female (we would change her name but she's a senior and she knows her name) 
Located in the Sidney NE area
8-10 years old
Sheltie/Cattle Dog/Shepherd(?) mix
Dog friendly
Cat friendly
Time is needed to allow her to decompress and warm up on her own terms.
House trained
Crate trained and knows some commands
Need super patient and chill home
Great off leash once she knows her boundaries. 
35lbs approximately 

BONDED WITH SAMMIE, MUST GO TOGETHER

Buster is looking for a calm and loving environment! She was the last of her 3 siblings to be captured and alluded is for months. Finally on February 22 2019 we were able to drug her and trap her in a kennel. Buster is still a work in progress but her current foster home has so many dogs with behavioral issues that Buster and her brother Sammie are spending significant time in their crates and we really just want more for them. 

Buster is still a bit leery and very pensive in some moments however she's come SO far since we caught her. Today, with the help of her Thunder Shirt (which she hasn't needed in over a year), lots of love and some patience she will sometimes seek out attention! Buster is bonded (healthy bond) with her more outgoing brother Sammie and really follows his lead. We would love them to find a foster or FURever home of their own, hopefully with less dogs than their current foster. The home needs to be ok being patient and showing them the love they need to continue to progress towards their potential awesomeness! Buster and Sammie are good with other dogs and cats, however Buster does better with other more submissive and or independent canine housemates.

This pair is truly beyond deserving and so amazing. After losing their human, being left to basically fend for themselves, being trapped, being mostly rehabbed and now living in a foster with so many other dogs. This dynamic duo deserves a fantastic home to live out the rest of their time on this planet. 
 

Due to having them so long in rescue and truly wanting to find them the most amazing home we have lowered their fee, as long as they are adopted together.

 $200.00 Adoption Fee 

(Which is considered a non refundable donation and being we are a 501c3 organization it is tax deductible. The fee itself is not negotiable, our vets don't negotiate and thus neither do we.)

If you think Buster and Sammie may be a good fit for your household and you're interested in helping please contact us!!! 

To Contact Us

Message us through our website http://www.highplainspaw.org

Message the Facebook Page at https://www.facebook.com/HighPlainsPAW

Fill out our Adoption Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/adoption-application

Fill out our Foster Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/foster-application

Email us at highplainspaw@gmail.com

Call our VOICEMAIL at (402)957-1578

WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY ALL OUR DOGS ARE LOCATED IN FOSTER HOMES. This means there is no place for you to go in person to view our dogs. We ask that an application be filled out and we will go from there!

animal.description:
Some doggos are worth melting for....

Hey fellas! So ice to meet you! I am Olaf, a 12 year old, male Poodle-Shih Tzu, and all of 13 lbs! I was found wandering the streets of Mexico before TAP rescued me. I have a beautiful before and after glam story and you can check it on TAP's IG! Matty looking streetos actually hide the most beautiful dogs inside, and I am proof of that! I am an older gentleman and the streets have given me one blind eye. It doesnt come in my way, unless I cant see ya in my rearview mirror and come underfoot. No lasting harm done, I pawmise! I am good on the leash and almost all bathroom trained. I will be neutered soon!

I am a spunky pup who will warm even the coldest of hearts. I am pretty easy-going and love attention when showered on me. I am getting the hang of a warm, cozy home after a fun stroll through the park and then cuddling with my people. This boy has been winning compliments about town and you cant ignore my cute face or snaggle teeth either! No one has caught on to my one-eyed-ness, and it sure doesnt limit me from hopping on your lap to cuddle. I have had trouble with some mild separation anxiety because of the stay-home situation my foster fam is in, but with conditioning, I am sure we can work on it. I am already pretty good in the crate! I am also a very friendly fella who adores people! I havent met kiddos yet. I am friendly towards dogs, specially the ones that look like me. I do very well at parks and dog beach too. I havent met kitties too, but I don't think I should have an issue. I dont even chase squirrels!

If you have any doubts regarding me, I'd say 'Let it gooooo"! I can pawmise to bring a happy ray of sunshine in your life. We all deserve some love and affection and I cant wait to share my life with my furever family! I would be happier with someone who stays home a lot and down for cuddling. My adoption fee is $150 and that includes spaying/neutering, shots, and microchip. If you want to take me home, please fill out the form on the website here https://theanimalpad.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
This precious puppy is Lucy (DOB Jan 2020), a pure bred Feist puppy looking for a home. Lucy was surrendered to us by her breeder when she as 4 weeks old. Unfortunatley her mother decided motherhood was not for her and attacked her litter. Lucy was the most wounded of the litter and the breeder could not afford her vet care. One of Lucy's eyes had to be removed and the other one is impaired. She can see some but it is limited sight. She also lost a bit of her tongue and has a bit of ear missing. That is the bad news. The good news is that Lucy has a zest for life like no other dog we have seen in a long time. She is super friendly and outgoing and her spirit has not been at all affected by what has happened to her. She runs and plays like a normal puppy. Lucy is active and will need a home that can meet her energy requirements. She will eventually wear herself out and become a sleepy cuddle bug but she does love to play. She is good with other dogs, is fine with cats and would be great for a home with kids that are looking for a dog that wouldn't mind some rough play. Lucy is up to date with shots, spayed, negative for heartworms/on prevention and is learning housebreaking, we are not quite there yet but she will hold it while being crated. If you think you are a fit for Lucy, please visit our website at www.myhstc.org to submit an adoption application.

Adoption fee is $85 which includes all vet work

We prescreen all applicants prior to a meeting. To be screened, please submit an adoption application at www.myhstc.org

animal.description:
Maverick
One Year Old
75 Pounds
Hound/Lab Mix
Housetrained
Loving and Lively 
Adoption Fee: TBD
Above Ground Visible Fence
Louisville Local Adoptions

"Shiny, Bright and Brilliant," that's a beautiful meaning of the name "Maverick." And... it happens to fit Maverick beautifully too! 

Maverick is certainly a handsome young man, no doubt. But below that handsome exterior is something very special. The sweetest soul you can imagine! 

When Maverick warms up to you he will be your best bud. Whether on a walk, watching Television together, playing with squeaky toys or just chillin', this baby will be a devoted companion. 

Did we mention cuddling? Yep, he's the best. And Maverick is a "Ball Sleeper." That's when a dog wraps himself in the tiniest, tightest ball you can imagine, reminding folks he won't take up much room on the couch or in the bed. 

Maverick has been very loved and cared for. And that's what his owners are praying for. Someone special just like Maverick! Maverick has not been cat tested but we think would do well with another sweet dog (depending on Meet and Greets) and older children. 

In addition to being extremely intelligent, a quick learner and highly devoted, Maverick also has a good sense of humor. Somehow he makes a Birthday Hat and other outfits look quite G-Q-ish. If YOU can see what we see in those shiny golden brown eyes let us know and we'll D.M. Maverick and let him know!

animal.description:
Meet Eddie!
Eddie has been with us for over two years! We can’t believe it. He is GREAT WITH KIDS and all around an amazing dog. He loves to play hard  and then will be happy relaxing on the couch. It’s time he finds a family that will love him as much as he deserves! 

Get your applications in!
https://www.causendogrescue.org/adoption-application.html 
?
?
?
We only do meet and greets for approved applications.

Adoption fee is $250.

All dogs will be Up-to-date on Shots, worming, Spayed/Neutered and Microchipped.   We will also do random, periodic vet checks to ensure all dogs adopted from us continue to have the best care.  We will check for any follow up visits needed and that they are on a monthly Heartworm Prevention.

If you rent or own a home, we prefer you to have a fenced in yard. 

Apartment living is also ok but prefer a fenced in area if close to the road.
All adults in the home will need to know they are getting a dog and will need to sign the adoption agreement.
We do not adopt to college students with multiple roommates. 
Military will need to provide a backup plan.
We require all pets in the home to be spay and/or neutered. Because too many dogs are being killed, due to there not being enough homes per dog in need. Only the lucky ones end up here.

animal.description:
Snapshot of Junie!

Size? Medium (35-50 lbs)
Age? 11 months
Activity Level? I play hard and snuggle hard!
Noise Level? I rarely bark!
Good with Dogs? I would LOVE a playmate!
Good with Cats? No cats please!
Good with Kids? Older kids only, if you please!
Good with Strangers? I love everyone!
Potty Trained? Working on it!
Crate Trained? I'll need some patient training to be crate trained, but I would love a family that's ok without crating me!

Interested? Learn more about Junie below!

About Junie:

My name is

Junie

and I'm almost 1 year old. I came from South Dakota in November to join my foster family. At first I was really nervous being in the big city. I had a hard time being on a leash and walking through doorways. I was really used to chasing whatever I wanted, so I made my family's cats a bit crazy. I'm still working on my impulse control. I do get it right sometime. I'm totally potty trained as long as you take me out every couple of hours.

I

love being outside playing and chasing squirrels. I especially like long walks in the woods. I'm learning to walk well on a leash, but you need to find the right one so I don't slip out to visit all my neighborhood friends and run around. I am especially snuggly, and sometimes think I'm a lap dog- even though I'm about 50 lbs. I really like to play tug of war and catch a ball (in the house, I'm still a bit nervous doing that outside). I really need to chew and will rip apart any stuffy to reveal it's fluffy insides.

I really love to be with my people and I follow my foster mom everywhere she goes. I'm terrified of a kennel so I sleep on my pillow next to my foster parents---though sometimes I wake up in their bed in the morning.

I'm a really smart dog and learn fast. I just need lots more training and treats and of course lots of love and attention!

I'm looking for my forever family, of course! I need to be *foster to adopt* first if you are looking to adopt me, because I still need a few vet appointments. :)

But, if you aren't quite ready to make the full leap to adoption, I would love to settle in with you as my foster!
Twin Cities Pet Rescue provides its foster families with food, supplies, and veterinary care for its animals. All you need to do is supply the love!

Adoption Fee: $475

MEET ME/ADOPT ME: If you'd like to arrange a meeting or begin the adoption process, please fill out an adoption application by visiting www.twincitiespetrescue.org/adopt/adopt-a-dog/ . A volunteer from Twin Cities Pet Rescue will contact you once your application is reviewed.

FOSTER HOMES NEEDED!!! Twin Cities Pet Rescue is a volunteer-run, foster home-based organization. We can only rescue as many animals as available foster homes. Please consider saving the life of an animal in need and become a volunteer foster home today. To become a foster, fill out a dog or cat foster application on the Twin Cities Pet Rescue website: www.twincitiespetrescue.org . There is little to no cost to foster an animal.

PLEASE NOTE: Twin Cities Pet Rescue does not adopt to homes further than 60 miles from the Minneapolis/St. Paul Metro Area.

VADOR (male)
Breed: shepherd mix (best guess)Age: approx. 6 monthsWeight: approx. 30 lbs.
Status - AVAILABLE
Experience - intermediate - advanced
Vador is a super sweet bouncy, energetic puppy who loves dogs of all ages, sizes and breed and will be great companion for most active homes. However, he can be shy and timid, a home with children under twelve will not be ideal for him.
Potential adopters should be prepared for puppy (potty & leash) training as well as time the time for a energetic puppy.
ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS & PROCEDURES
Mutt Match L.A. does not adopt out of state nor do we adopt on a first come first serve basis but rather to the home that is best suited for each particular dog and breed. An application, home check, contract and adoption fee are required for all adoptions. All dogs will be, or required to be, spayed/neutered, current on vaccinations and microchipped before adoption. Most of our dogs are from local LA area shelters, we generally have no prior history for them.
Adoption fees vary between $400 - $500 for puppies 8 weeks - 5 years, $350 6 - 9 years and $300 for dogs over 9 years. Adoption fee covers spay/neuter, vaccinations, microchip, wellness check and of course all the love and daily care we take with each dog before they are adopted.
We believe a well behaved dog is a happy dog and companion. Therefore, we require at least one session with one of our recommended behaviorists for a reduced fee which is not included in the adoption fee.
We are a busy fully functioning rescue and facility, unfortunately, we do not take requests for more photos and/or video. The photos you currently see are what we currently have and are updated as we recevie new photos. For additional information or questions, please email us at info@muttmatchla.org. To submit an application, please visit us at www.muttmatchla.org. Mutt Match L.A. is an all volunteer rescue, please allow at least 48 hours for a returned response of all inquires.
Thank you! We look forward to hearing from you soon.

animal.description:
NO LONGER ACCEPTING APPLICATIONS!!

Meet Teddy. Teddy and his brother, Franklin, are the result of two family dogs living together who were not spayed or neutered. Their owners are older and not attentive to their dogs, who mostly live outside. They didn't even realize their female dog was pregnant, and she would have been on her own if Good Samaritans were not looking out for her. Teddy's mom dug out a bunker-type area inside an old, dilapidated shed on the property to protect and nurse her pups. She was smart to find a quiet place with cover and no traffic.

Thankfully, a Good Samaritan was watching out for her and discovered the puppies. They started feeding her and making sure she had fresh water and blankets to nurse the puppies. They kept the puppies with mom until they were six weeks old and then worked to get all the dogs released to rescue. The owners surrendered the puppies but wanted to keep their parents. They agreed to get them spayed and neutered, so there will be no more puppies, and we will continue to reach out and monitor their level of care.

Teddy is about eight weeks old and weighs 9-10 lbs. He and his brother Franklin now live together in a foster home. We think his mom is some mix of Chesapeake Bay Retriever or German Shorthaired Lab mix, and dad may be a Pointer mix with his gorgeous snow-white coat. It's so rare for us to know who both parents are, and these dogs are clearly fluffier than your typical Lab. We expect Teddy to be a large dog, about 50-65lbs when fully grown. He has already transitioned to puppy kibble and is being crate trained. During the day, both pups have a large penned area to romp and play in with access to their crate. Their foster parents have started closing the crate for short periods to get them accustomed to containment and begin the work on potty training.

This gorgeous fluffy boy needs a fun, active family ready for puppy mode and committed to training. He is very cute now but will grow to be a large, energetic dog who needs a capable handler. He really enjoys playtime with his brother, so a family with another social, playful pup in the home would be ideal for Teddy to learn from.

Preference will be given to families with:

Large dog experience

Flexible, puppy-friendly schedule

Another social dog in the home

Active family

Will only be adopted to families in the DC metro and surrounding area

Teddy is still too young to be neutered, but having him neutered at the appropriate age will be required as part of his adoption terms. We will require that proof of neuter is provided to the rescue.

Teddy will be coming to N. VA on 2/6/21 and we'd like him to go straight home.

Apply today!

BREED ESTIMATE: Retriever/Pointer mix
GENDER: Male
APPROXIMATE WEIGHT: 9 lbs (will be a larger dog 55lb - 70lbs fully grown)
APPROXIMATE AGE: ~ 7.5 weeks
COAT TYPE: Medium - fluffy
ADOPTION FEE: $400
OTHER INFO: utd on shots/microchipped
LOCATION: Rock Hill, SC - Coming to N. VA on 2/6/21

FOR MORE INFO OR TO ADOPT: Please go to https://adopt.worthydog.org and complete the application.

You can also help save dogs like this one by becoming a foster, providing a rescue dog with a temporary home and giving them the love and care they need until they are permanently adopted. Every person who fosters is directly responsible for saving the life of a dog, because we can only save as many dogs as we have foster families available to welcome them into their homes. If you think you might be interested in becoming a foster and want to learn more, please go to https://foster.worthydog.org and fill out an application.

Worthy Dog Rescue is an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue that primarily adopts to families in the DC Metro area.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Casey. I’m a 1yr old German Shepherd Mix whose one true purpose in life is to cuddle with you forever and ever. I weigh a little over 40lbs and am the queen of giving you: “puppy dog eyes”. 

My origin story may not have the best of beginnings, but as my foster mom knows, I have tried my best to make the most out of still being the easy-going, happy go-lucky girl that I am.  As your pup, I will always be by your side (literally and figuratively!). I know I’m slightly bigger than most “lap dogs” but that will not stop me from cuddling up next to you or getting on your lap to give and receive all the love. Once I get to know you after a few snuggle sessions, it means that I will do everything in my power to defend you and our home. This just means that if I hear something that doesn’t sound right or sense danger, I will make my presence known, otherwise, I’m a relatively quiet dog. I don’t bark unless I absolutely have to because I believe that resting my vocal chords is very important. 

I do have a small aversion to loud noises because they make me a bit jumpy and I do tend to hesitate just a bit when meeting new people, but once I get to know you and you show me love (aka give me a treat or some belly rubs), that all goes away! 

I am completely potty-trained, do very well in my kennel, and I know commands like “sit” and “come”. I am very receptive to hearing my name and the commands that I know when called. I am currently working on learning commands like “stay” and tricks like “spin” but, honestly, why learn it when I know my foster mom is going to end up still giving me the treats anyway? I don’t mind cats or other dogs at all and love hanging out with humans of all sizes. 

I am up to date on all my vaccinations, am heartworm negative, and am going to go and get spayed in early February of this year! I am an amazing girl and would love to join and be with you in my forever home!

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

*Any breed labels used by Take Paws Rescue, its employees/volunteers, or on vet records provided cannot be guaranteed.  Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

animal.description:
Hello, adopters. 
This is Petra here. Tonight I heard volunteers talk about updating pictures and trying to capture personalities. So, apparently, I don't smile enough. So, I improved my game tonight. I wasn't very fond of the fluffy scarf they threw on me, but sitting with volunteer Kris was pretty amazing and brought me so much happiness. She was doing paperwork and sipping her drink. I just kept giving a nudge as a reminder that I would really like some love. I was in heaven. Yeah, I can visual myself making that smooth transition right into a home. 

If you follow The A.R.K. page, you already know my BFF Pugsly. She puts a smile on my face and reminds me to have fun in life. She also loves people.. In fact, she had a hard time peeling herself away for a Kodak moment, but she ended up succeeding. I encouraged her to put on a cheesy smile too. I hope our plan works. We are so ready for a home. 

We are inseparable, so we leaving a shelter together. So, if you are a family willing to invest time in two lovely, six-year-old girls AND have a fenced in yard, then please send in an application. Even if you share this post, you may just help us find the perfect home. 

Oh, yeah, Kris just reminded me to share with The Ark followers that we keep a clean kennel (apparently that is important to people). She also wanted me to tell you that she had a cookie on the edge of the desk, and I was respectful of space while I was sitting by her. I didn't try to snatch it.

So, I guess that is all for tonight. If I missed anything, just contact The ARK. They will answer any questions that you may have. The volunteers and staff have become family. It will be hard to say our goodbyes when we are adopted, but we know our future adopters have a good chance of sending an update for the volunteers, at least at Christmas time. I see lots of my old pals on cards in the lobby. 

I have rambled long enough. See you soon!

Petra & Pugsly

Email to arkanimalshelter@yahoo.com. Once your application is approved, you will be contacted for a meet and greet.

Questions? 309-246-4275

animal.description:
Boomer is a sweet, more calm lab. He loves butt scratches! He loves them so much that he does a little dance when he gets them. It's soo cute! His fur is baby soft and he has the cool unique stripe down his back. Boomer came to us as a stray but seems to be looking for his family. He is about 3 years old and heartworm positive. He will need to go through heartworm treatment either with a foster or in a foster to adopt home.
Please call the shelter at (706) 795-2868 to schedule a meet and greet. Madison Oglethorpe Animal Shelter is a non-profit shelter serving over 720 square miles. We are open intake, meaning we can not turn away animals from either county we serve. Our shelter intakes double or triple it's capacity every month so it is essential we place animals quickly into adoptive homes. Since so many animals enter the shelter we often don't have enough volunteers to write an individual bio for each. Please feel free to call the shelter Wednesday-Sunday to inquire about the animal you are interested in. 706-795-2868. Viewing and adoption hours at our shelter are Wednesday through Sunday from 12 PM to 5 PM. All adoption fees include age-appropriate vaccinations, flea treatment, deworming, and spay or neuter, microchip, and adoption packet. Fees: Dogs over 4 months old: $100 Puppies under 4 months: $125. Cats and Kittens are $75 ($65 without microchip). For your convenience you can fill out an adoption application for any of our current residents at www.moaspets.com. Join us on Facebook at https://www.facebook.com/moaspets. It's a great way to stay up to the minute on the furry 4 legged friends we have looking for a loving forever home. We are located at: 1888 Colbert Danielsville Rd Danielsville, GA 30633 706-795-2868 NOTE: Our adoptions are first come first served, simply filling out an application does not mean the animal will be held for you, you must come meet the animal in person in order to be considered for adoption. If you rent you must bring your lease or a letter from your landlord stating you may adopt.

Hi everyone my name is Crew! I am a sweet, energetic guy who loves to be around my foster parents. I play fairly rough and would do best in a house without small children.
